{"title_page": "Central and Eastern European Online Library", "text_new": "{{primary sources|date=July 2017}}\n[[File:CEEOL logo.png|thumb|Logo]]\nThe '''Central and Eastern European Online Library''' (CEEOL) is a repository of full text indexed documents in the fields of Humanities and Social Science publications from and about [[Central and Eastern Europe]]. The collections include native language sources from and about Central, East and Southeast Europe's humanities and social sciences in the form of journal articles, eBooks and [[Grey Literature]].\n\nThe subject areas include [[anthropology]], [[culture]] and [[society]], [[economy]], [[gender studies]], [[history]], [[Judaic studies]], [[fine arts]], [[literature]], [[linguistics]], [[political| political sciences]] and [[social sciences]], [[philosophy]], [[religion]], [[law]]\n\nUpdated daily, the CEEOL coverage grows by approximately 4,000 newly included journal articles every month. A significant number of the included journals are represented with a complete archival collection. The CEEOL eBook collection development started in 2016 offering an ever-growing number of eBooks, as well as backlists of the publishing houses. The CEEOL Grey Literature Collection project provides researchers with access to more than 4,000 Grey Literature items.\n\nCEEOL may be considered as the virtual successor of Palais Jalta \u2013 Ost/West Europ\u00e4isches Kulturzentrum eV (East/West European Cultural Centre \u201cPalais Jalta\u201d), a non-profit organisation, that  organized a significant number of symposia, political and cultural debates, and exhibitions between 1989-2003 with a focus on Central, East and Southeast European societies, their cultures and issues.<ref>Bea Klotz, The Central and Eastern European Online Library, in: The Serials Librarian, Volume 53, Issue 1 & 2 August 2007, pages 191\u2013201 (http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.1300/J123v53n01_15?redirect=1)</ref>\n\nThe first release of CEEOL was developed in 1999 and was operated until the end of 2015 by Questa.Soft GmbH in Frankfurt am Main. A redeveloped, cloud-based CEEOL repository was launched on 1 January 2016 and is operated by the Central and Eastern European Online Library GmbH (CEEOL GmbH)  in [[Frankfurt am Main]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Robert Murray Davis, East Goes West. New Ventures in Eastern European Publishing, in: World Literature Today, May\u2013August 2004, pages 53\u201355\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.ceeol.com/}}\n*[https://www.faz.net/aktuell/rhein-main/kultur/frankfurter-online-bibliothek-boomt-waehrend-corona-krise-16728706.html Article] in German by Niklas Zimmermann, Digitales Fenster nach Osten - Online-Bibliothek zu Osteuropa, in: [[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung|Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung,]]17.04.2020\n* [http://www.fr-online.de/in_und_ausland/politik/dossiers/50_jahre_eu/?sid=56d81dc76f3d7ca6c40e68b18e5b23d0&em_cnt=1099557 Article] in German by Anita Strecker, Osteuropa f\u00e4ngt in Oberrad an, in: [[Frankfurter Rundschau]], 21.03.2007\n* [http://www.fr-online.de/in_und_ausland/kultur_und_medien/literatur/buchmesse_2007/1222985_Meine-Buchmesse-II-Alle-wieder-da.html Article] in German by Wolfgang Klotz, Alle wieder da, in: Frankfurter Rundschau, 10.10.2007\n* [http://www.faz.net/aktuell/rhein-main/palais-jalta-hoert-auf-freier-entschluss-des-ost-westeuropaeischen-kulturzentrums-1130862.html Article] in German by Gerd Koenen und Wolfgang Klotz, \u201ePalais Jalta\u201c h\u00f6rt auf, Freier Entschlu\u00df des Ost-Westeurop\u00e4ischen Kulturzentrums in: [[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]], 09.10.2003\n\n[[Category:Web archiving initiatives]]\n[[Category:Geographic region-oriented digital libraries]]\n[[Category:German digital libraries]]\n[[Category:Databases in Germany]]\n[[Category:Bibliographic databases and indexes]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2000]]\n", "text_old": "{{primary sources|date=July 2017}}\n[[File:CEEOL logo.png|thumb|Logo]]\nThe '''Central and Eastern European Online Library''' (CEEOL) is a repository of full text indexed documents in the fields of Humanities and Social Science publications from and about [[Central and Eastern Europe]]. The collections include native language sources from and about Central, East and Southeast Europe's humanities and social sciences in the form of journal articles, eBooks and [[Grey Literature]].\n\nThe subject areas include [[anthropology]], [[culture]] and [[society]], [[economy]], [[gender studies]], [[history]], [[Judaic studies]], [[fine arts]], [[literature]], [[linguistics]], [[political| political sciences]] and [[social sciences]], [[philosophy]], [[religion]], [[law]]\n\nUpdated daily, the CEEOL coverage grows by approximately 4,000 newly included journal articles every month. A significant number of the included journals are represented with a complete archival collection. The CEEOL eBook collection development started in 2016 offering an ever-growing number of eBooks, as well as backlists of the publishing houses. The CEEOL Grey Literature Collection project provides researchers with access to more than 3,000 Grey Literature items.\n\nCEEOL may be considered as the virtual successor of Palais Jalta \u2013 Ost/West Europ\u00e4isches Kulturzentrum eV (East/West European Cultural Centre \u201cPalais Jalta\u201d), a non-profit organisation, that  organized a significant number of symposia, political and cultural debates, and exhibitions between 1989-2003 with a focus on Central, East and Southeast European societies, their cultures and issues.<ref>Bea Klotz, The Central and Eastern European Online Library, in: The Serials Librarian, Volume 53, Issue 1 & 2 August 2007, pages 191\u2013201 (http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.1300/J123v53n01_15?redirect=1)</ref>\n\nThe first release of CEEOL was developed in 1999 and was operated until the end of 2015 by Questa.Soft GmbH in Frankfurt am Main. A redeveloped, cloud-based CEEOL repository was launched on 1 January 2016 and is operated by the Central and Eastern European Online Library GmbH (CEEOL GmbH)  in [[Frankfurt am Main]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Robert Murray Davis, East Goes West. New Ventures in Eastern European Publishing, in: World Literature Today, May\u2013August 2004, pages 53\u201355\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.ceeol.com/}}\n* [http://www.fr-online.de/in_und_ausland/politik/dossiers/50_jahre_eu/?sid=56d81dc76f3d7ca6c40e68b18e5b23d0&em_cnt=1099557 Article] in German by Anita Strecker, Osteuropa f\u00e4ngt in Oberrad an, in: [[Frankfurter Rundschau]], 21.03.2007\n* [http://www.fr-online.de/in_und_ausland/kultur_und_medien/literatur/buchmesse_2007/1222985_Meine-Buchmesse-II-Alle-wieder-da.html Article] in German by Wolfgang Klotz, Alle wieder da, in: Frankfurter Rundschau, 10.10.2007\n* [http://www.faz.net/aktuell/rhein-main/palais-jalta-hoert-auf-freier-entschluss-des-ost-westeuropaeischen-kulturzentrums-1130862.html Article] in German by Gerd Koenen und Wolfgang Klotz, \u201ePalais Jalta\u201c h\u00f6rt auf, Freier Entschlu\u00df des Ost-Westeurop\u00e4ischen Kulturzentrums in: [[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]], 09.10.2003\n\n[[Category:Web archiving initiatives]]\n[[Category:Geographic region-oriented digital libraries]]\n[[Category:German digital libraries]]\n[[Category:Databases in Germany]]\n[[Category:Bibliographic databases and indexes]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2000]]\n", "name_user": "BeaKlotz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:- newly published article on CEEOL in the Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_and_Eastern_European_Online_Library"}
{"title_page": "Dhananjaya Y. Chandrachud", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian judge}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =Hon'ble Dr. Justice\n| name = Dhananjaya Yeshwant Chandrachud\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = File:Justice D.Y. Chandrachud.jpg\n| image_size = 220px\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| office = [[Judge]] of [[Supreme Court of India]]\n| term_start = 13 May 2016\n| term_end = \n| appointer = [[Pranab Mukherjee]]\n| office1 = [[Allahabad High Court#List of Chief Justices|45th]] [[Chief Justice]] of [[Allahabad High Court]]\n| term_start1 = 31 October 2013\n| term_end1 = 12 May 2016<ref name=\"sc\">{{Cite web |url=http://supremecourtofindia.nic.in/chief-justice-judges |title=Supreme Court of India: Chief Justice & Judges |website=supremecourtofindia.nic.in |language=en |access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n| appointer1 = [[Pranab Mukherjee]]\n| predecessor1 = \n| successor1 = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1959|11|11}}<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allahabadhighcourt.in/service/judgeDetail.jsp?id=203|title=Hon'ble Dr. Justice Dhananjaya Yashwant Chandrachud (CJ)|website=www.allahabadhighcourt.in}}</ref>\n| birth_place = \n| alma_mater = [[St. Columba's School, Delhi]]<br />[[University of Delhi]] ([[B.A.|BA]], [[LLB]])<br />[[Harvard University]] ([[LLM]], [[Doctor of Juridical Science|S.J.D.]])\n| children = 2<ref>{{cite news|title=Justice Chandrachud: the man who doesn't mince words|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/justice-chandrachud-the-man-who-doesn-t-mince-words/cid/1670365|publisher=Telegraph India|accessdate=28 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Collegium system needs reconsideration, says former Supreme Court judge AK Sikri|url=https://theprint.in/india/collegium-system-needs-reconsideration-says-former-supreme-court-judge-ak-sikri/358080/|publisher=The Print|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n| nominator = [[T. S. Thakur]]\n| nominator1 = [[P. Sathasivam]]\n| office2 = [[Judge]] of [[Bombay High Court]]\n| termstart2 = 29 March 2000\n| termend2 = 30 October 2013\n| appointer2 = [[Kocheril Raman Narayanan]]\n| nominator2 = [[Adarsh Sein Anand]]\n}}\n\n'''Dhananjaya Yeshwant Chandrachud''' (born 11 November 1959) is currently a [[Judge]] of  [[Supreme Court of India]]. He is former [[Chief Justice]] of the [[Allahabad High Court]] and a former judge of [[Mumbai High Court|Bombay High Court]].<ref name=\"allahabadhighcourt.in\">{{cite web|url=http://allahabadhighcourt.in/service/judgeDetail.jsp?id=203|title=Hon'ble&nbsp;Dr.&nbsp;Justice&nbsp;Dhananjaya Yashwant Chandrachud&nbsp;(CJ)|work=allahabadhighcourt.in/indexhigh.html|accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vmslaw.edu/sympo.htm|title=Millennium Laws For India Inc.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070806180624/http://www.vmslaw.edu/sympo.htm|archivedate=6 August 2007|url-status=dead|accessdate=23 July 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lawcommissionofindia.nic.in/adr_conf/chandrachud3.pdf |title=Mediiation \u2013 realizing the potential and designin implementation strategies |author=Dr. Hon'ble Justice Shananjaya Y. Chandrachud |website=Lawcommissionofindia.nic.in |accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education==\nChandrachud was born on 11 November 1959.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> His father [[Yeshwant Vishnu Chandrachud]] was the longest serving [[Chief Justice of India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/justice-chandrachud-keeps-running-into-fathers-rulings/articleshow/65250527.cms|title=Justice Chandrachud keeps running into father's rulings}}</ref> His mother Prabha was a classical musician. After attending [[Cathedral and John Connon School]], [[Mumbai]] and [[St. Columba's School, Delhi]], Chandrachud graduated with honours in Economics and Mathematics from [[St. Stephen's College, Delhi|St. Stephen's College]], [[New Delhi]] in 1979.<ref>{{cite web | title =Dhananjaya Y. Chandrachud Dr. Justice | work =Achievers | publisher =Old Columbans' Association | url =http://www.oldcolumban.net/achievers.html | accessdate =9 April 2012 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120226125705/http://www.oldcolumban.net/achievers.html | archivedate =26 February 2012 | df =dmy-all }}</ref> He then obtained his [[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]] degree from [[Delhi University]] in 1982, followed by an [[Master of Laws|LL.M.]] degree from [[Harvard University]] in 1983. At Harvard, he studied on the prestigious Inlaks Scholarship, and received the Joseph H Beale prize.<ref name=\"inlaks\">{{Cite web |url=http://inlaksfoundation.org/Alumni.aspx?sort=old&Type=A&SortAlpha=D |title=Inlaks Shivdasani Foundation: Alumni |date=2010 |website=inlaksfoundation.org |access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref> He went on to receive his Doctorate of Juridical Sciences (S.J.D.), from [[Harvard University]] in 1986.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-10-31/allahabad/43559442_1_chief-justice-bombay-high-court-oath |title=Harvard alumni Hon'ble DY Chandrachud to take oath as Hon'ble chief justice of high court |work=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref> His doctoral thesis was on Affirmative Action; it considered the law in a comparative framework.<ref name=\"hawaii.edu\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hawaii.edu/news/2018/05/31/chandrachud-global-social-justice-lecture/|title=India supreme court justice offers public lecture on global social justice|last=News|first=U. H.|website=University of Hawai\u02bbi System News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref> He had been conferred with an ''Honoris Causa'' [[Legum Doctor|LL.D]]. by [[University of Lucknow|Lucknow University]] in 2015.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/pdf/AnnualReports/Supreme_High_Court_AR_English_2018-19.pdf|title=Indian Judiciary : Annual Report 2018-19|first2=|publisher=The Supreme Court of India, New Delhi|year=2019|isbn=|location=|pages=21}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nChandrachud studied law at Delhi university in 1982 at a time when few jobs were available to young law graduates. He worked for a while, as a junior advocate assisting lawyers and judges, including some memorable briefings that he did for [[Fali Nariman]]. Thereafter he joined [[Harvard law school]]. After graduating Harvard, Chandrachud first worked at [[Sullivan and Cromwell]], a law firm. Chandrachud describes this as \"sheer fluke\" due to the strong pecking order that existed at that time, and a strong bias against Indians and similar developing countries.<ref>{{cite news |title=The evolution of India's legal system - a lecture by Justice D.Y. Chandrachud |publisher=Bloomberg Quint |date=16 December 2017}}</ref> 1986 onwards, national law schools were established in a number of cities in India. He was designated as Senior Advocate by the [[Bombay High Court]] in June 1998. From 1998, he was Additional Solicitor General of India until his appointment as a Judge.\nHe became a judge at the Bombay High Court from 29 March 2000 until his appointment as Chief Justice of the Allahabad High Court. During this time, he was also Director of Maharashtra Judicial Academy. All through, he practised law at the Supreme Court of India and the Bombay High Court. He was Chief Justice of the [[Allahabad High Court]] from 31 October 2013 until appointment to the [[Supreme Court of India]]. He was appointed Judge of the Supreme Court of India on 13 May 2016.<ref name=\"supremecourt\">{{cite web |title=Chief Justice and Judges |url=https://www.supremecourtofindia.nic.in/chief-justice-judges |website=www.supremecourtofindia.nic.in |publisher=Supreme court of India |accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe continues to be a visiting Professor of Comparative Constitutional law at the [[University of Mumbai]] and [[Oklahoma University|Oklahoma University School of Law]], USA. He has delivered lectures at the [[Australian National University]], Deakin University, Melbourne Law School, Harvard Law School, [[Yale Law School]], William S. Richardson School of Law at the University of Hawaii and the [[University of Witwatersrand]], South Africa. He has been a speaker at conferences organised by bodies of the United Nations including [[UNHCR|United Nations High Commission on Human Rights]], International Labour Organisation and United Nations Environmental Program, the World Bank and Asian Development Bank.<ref name=\"sc\"/>\n<ref name=\"allahabadhighcourt.in\" /> He delivered lecture titled \"Global Constitutionalism in the Age of Transnational Judicial Conversations in Human Rights\", organised by Supreme Court of Hawai\u02bbi and the University of Hawai\u02bbi on 6 June 2018.<ref name=\"hawaii.edu\" />\n\n== Notable speeches ==\nJustice Dhananjaya has been a speaker at conferences organised by bodies of the United Nations including United Nations High Commission on Human Rights,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pacific.ohchr.org/final_conclusions.htm|title=OHCHR Regional Office for the Pacific Region|website=pacific.ohchr.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> International Labour Organisation and United Nations Environmental Program, the World Bank and Asian Development Bank. He delivered a lecture titled \u201cGlobal Constitutionalism in the Age of Transnational Judicial Conversations in Human Rights\u201d, organised by Supreme Court of Hawai\u2019i and the University of Hawai\u2019i on 6 June 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hawaii.edu/news/2018/05/31/chandrachud-global-social-justice-lecture/|title=India supreme court justice offers public lecture on global social justice {{!}} University of Hawai\u02bbi System News|last=News|first=U. H.|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> He has delivered numerous speeches in India at premier law institutions as well as events organized by civil society. His most recent speeches include: \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Speeches\n!Date\n!Topic\n!Location\n|-\n|September 2018\n|Rule of Law in a Constitutional Democracy<ref>{{Citation|title=19th Annual Bodh Raj Sawhny Memorial Oration 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YVvRr0ZzRPM|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|19th Annual Bodh Raj Sawhney Memorial, NLUD, Delhi<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nludelhi.ac.in/UploadedImages/a47c94e1-8cd4-48de-81ba-be103bc976a3.pdf|title=NLUD invite|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n|December 2018\n|Law and Storytelling<ref>{{Citation|title=Justice D Y Chandrachud|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pAKZ_IlKeJI|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|Increasing Diversity by Increasing Access (IDIA), Delhi\n|-\n|December 2018\n|Why the Constitution matters<ref>{{Citation|title=Lecture by Hon'ble Justice Dr. D. Y. Chandrachud, on Why Constitution Matters|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vr1Dc_-ZKbQ|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|[[Bombay High Court]]\n|-\n|February 2019\n|Law, Culture and Identity\n|[[Kala Ghoda Arts Festival]], Bombay<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kalaghodaassociation.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Kgaf2019-Booklet-07-02-2019.pdf|title=2019 Invite - Arts Festival|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n|March 2019\n|A Borrowed Constitution: A fact or a myth?<ref>{{Citation|title=\"A Borrowed Constitution: Fact Or Myth\" {{!}} Nani Palkhiwala Lecture By Justice DY Chandrachud {{!}} Part 1|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mNKeSJ6aOKk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|Annual Nani Palkhiwala Lecture, Delhi<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/constitution-contemplated-strong-centre-for-preserving-stability-of-india-chandrachud/1505760|title=Constitution contemplated strong Centre for preserving stability of India: Chandrachud|website=https://www.outlookindia.com/|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|-\n|April 2019\n|Green Law Lecture<ref>{{Citation|title=Green Law Lecture by Hon'ble Justice Dr D.Y. Chandrachud|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oNrcNu7jufY|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|[[O. P. Jindal Global University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jgu.edu.in/blog/2019/03/27/jindal-global-university-launches-environmental-law-course-one-year-masters-programme-in-collaboration-with-wwf-india/|title=Jindal Global University Launches Environmental Law Course: One year Masters Programme in Collaboration with WWF-India|last=JGUAdmin|date=2019-03-27|website=The Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|-\n|August 2019\n|Imagining Freedom Through Art<ref>{{Citation|title=Imagining Freedom Through Art with Justice Dhanjaya Chandrachud|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j4bIXgJI-Xc|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|Literature Live, Annual Independence Day Lecture, Bombay<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gupte|first=Masoom|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/lit-live-i-day-lecture-justice-chandrachud-takes-the-mic-will-encourage-people-to-imagine-freedom-via-art/articleshow/70701299.cms|title=Lit Live I-Day Lecture: Justice Chandrachud takes the mic, will encourage people to imagine freedom via art|date=2019-08-16|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|}\nMore recently, in December 2019, he delivered a speech titled \u2018Adding Nuance to Human Rights Discourse\u2019<ref>{{Citation|title=Scrutinize Those In Power Every Day: Justice Chandrachud -Human Rights Day 2019 Speech|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mZQfCO4p1cs|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> where he highlighted the importance of democratic scrutiny, procedures and deliberation as an important facet of human rights protection. \n\nIn February 2020, he delivered the speech titled \u2018The hues that make India: from plurality to pluralism'<ref>{{Citation|title=Democracy's true test is the ability to allow individuals to voice their opinion:Justice Chandrachud|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oIW4fhXZMeg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> at the P D Desai Memorial Lecture in Gujarat. He stated:<blockquote>\u2026the employment of state machinery to curb dissent instils fear and creates a chilling atmosphere on free speech which violates the rule of law and detracts from the constitutional vision of a pluralist society\u2026The true test of a democracy is its ability to ensure the creation and protection of spaces where every individual can voice their opinion without the fear of retribution\u2026A state committed to the rule of law ensures that the state apparatus is not employed to curb legitimate and peaceful protest but to create spaces conducive for deliberation. Within the bounds of law, liberal democracies ensure that their citizens enjoy the right to express their views in every conceivable manner, including the right to protest and express dissent against prevailing laws. The blanket labelling of such dissent as \u2018anti-national\u2019 or \u2018anti-democratic\u2019 strikes at the heart of our commitment to the protection of constitutional values and the promotion of a deliberative democracy.</blockquote>In an impassioned appeal to pluralism and the celebration of diversity, he stated:<blockquote>The framers of the Constitution rejected the notion of a Hindu India and a Muslim India. They recognised only the Republic of India\u2026A united India is not one characterized by a single identity devoid of its rich plurality, both of cultures and of values. National unity denotes a shared culture of values and a commitment to the fundamental ideals of the Constitution in which all individuals are guaranteed not just the fundamental rights but also conditions for their free and safe exercise. Pluralism depicts not merely a commitment to the preservation of diversity, but a commitment to the fundamental postulates of individual and equal dignity. In this sense, pluralism furthers the basic postulates of the Constitution and nourishes and provides content to the goal of national unity...No single individual or institution can claim a monopoly over the idea of India\u2026what is of utmost relevance today is our ability and commitment to preserve, conserve and build on the rich pluralistic history we have inherited.</blockquote>The speech was reported <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indialegallive.com/top-news-of-the-day/news/dissent-not-anti-national-says-justice-dy-chandrachud-89239|title=Dissent Not Anti-National excerpts/ Justice PD Desai Memorial Lecture 2020|last=Legal|first=India|date=2020-02-22|website=India Legal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/blanket-labelling-of-dissent-as-antinational-hurts-ethos-of/1735088|title=Blanket labelling of dissent as anti-national hurts ethos of|website=https://www.outlookindia.com/|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://punemirror.indiatimes.com/news/india/dissent-a-safety-valve-justice-chandrachud/articleshow/74156371.cms|title=Dissent a safety valve: Justice Chandrachud|last=Feb 16|first=PTI {{!}} Updated:|last2=2020|website=Pune Mirror|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20|last3=Ist|first3=08:07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/hindu-india-and-a-muslim-indiajustice-chandrachud-152796|title='The Framers of Constitution Rejected The Notion of a Hindu India And a Muslim India':Justice Chandrachud [Read Full Text Of Speech]|last=NETWORK|first=LIVELAW NEWS|date=2020-02-16|website=www.livelaw.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> as a plea to protect the right to dissent in a free and democratic society.\n\n==Notable judgments==\n\nAs a judge of the Supreme Court, Justice Chandrachud has been on the highest number of Constitution Benches (five judges or more) constituted to hear matters before the Indian Supreme Court.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.barandbench.com/columns/constituting-constitution-benches-of-the-supreme-court-an-analysis|title=Constituting Constitution Benches of the Supreme Court: An analysis|last=Bench|first=Bar &|website=Bar and Bench - Indian Legal news|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> During his tenure at the Supreme Court, he has delivered a large number of landmark judgements on Indian constitutional law, comparative constitutional law, human rights law, gender justice, public interest litigation, commercial law and criminal law.\n\n=== Privacy ===\nForemost among his notable judgments is his authorship of the lead opinion in [[Justice K. S. Puttaswamy (Retd.) and Anr. vs Union Of India And Ors.]] as part of a unanimous nine-judge Bench decision of the Indian Supreme Court which affirmed that the right to privacy is a constitutionally guaranteed right under the Indian Constitution.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2012/35071/35071_2012_Judgement_24-Aug-2017.pdf|title=Privacy judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Justice Chandrachud grounded the right to privacy in dignity, liberty, autonomy, bodily and mental integrity, self-determination and across a spectrum of protected rights. Writing for himself and three other judges, he stated:<blockquote>Dignity cannot exist without privacy. Both reside within the inalienable values of life, liberty and freedom which the Constitution has recognised. Privacy is the ultimate expression of the sanctity of the individual. It is a constitutional value which straddles across the spectrum of fundamental rights and protects for the individual a zone of choice and self-determination.<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>One expert on constitutional law hailed the decision<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://indconlawphil.wordpress.com/2017/08/27/the-supreme-courts-right-to-privacy-judgment-i-foundations/|title=The Supreme Court\u2019s Right to Privacy Judgment \u2013 I: Foundations|last=Bhatia|first=Gautam|date=2017-08-27|website=Indian Constitutional Law and Philosophy|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> as \u201ca historic and landmark verdict of our times\u201d which \u201cwill have a profound impact upon our legal and constitutional landscape for years to come.\u201d He stated that the:<blockquote>\u2026judgment deserves to be a landmark, not only in the annals of Indian constitutional jurisprudence, but across the world. The verdict locates privacy in the grand sweep of democracy and within the core human values of autonomy, dignity, and freedom, while also placing it within the realm of the concrete, the flesh-and-blood relationship between the individual and the State.<ref name=\":1\" /></blockquote>The judgment is also noteworthy for Justice Chandrachud\u2019s observations on sexual autonomy and privacy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/law/justice-chandrachud-judgment-right-to-privacy|title=Key Highlights of Justice Chandrachud's Judgment in the Right to Privacy Case|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In 2013, a two judge Bench of the Supreme Court of India in [[Suresh Kumar Koushal v. Naz Foundation]] upheld [[Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code]] which criminalized carnal intercourse against the order of nature. Justice Chandrachud referred to the decision as striking \u201ca discordant note which directly bears upon the evolution of the constitutional jurisprudence on the right to privacy.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> He observed that the decision was wrong as \u201cthe purpose of elevating certain rights to the stature of guaranteed fundamental rights is to insulate their exercise from the disdain of majorities, whether ''legislative or popular''.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> He concluded by disagreeing \u201cwith the manner in which Koushal has dealt with the privacy \u2013 dignity-based claims of LGBT persons\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> and held that:<blockquote>The test of popular acceptance does not furnish a valid basis to disregard rights which are conferred with the sanctity of constitutional protection.\u00a0 Discrete and insular minorities face grave dangers of discrimination for the simple reason that their views, beliefs or way of life does not accord with the \u2018mainstream\u2019. Yet in a democratic constitution founded on the rule of law, their rights are as sacred as those conferred on other citizens to protect their freedoms and liberties. Sexual orientation is an essential attribute of privacy. Discrimination against an individual on the basis of sexual orientation is deeply offensive to the dignity and self-worth of the individual.<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>The above observations played a role<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/law/justice-chandrachud-judgment-right-to-privacy|title=Key Highlights of Justice Chandrachud's Judgment in the Right to Privacy Case|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|date=2015-06-05|title=Queer Rights and the Puttaswamy Judgment|url=https://www.epw.in/journal/2017/51/privacy-after-puttaswamy-judgment/queer-rights-and-puttaswamy-judgment.html|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|language=en|volume=52|issue=51|pages=7\u20138}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rsrr.in/2018/11/16/implications-puttaswamy-aadhar-section-377/|title=IMPLICATIONS OF JUSTICE K.S PUTTASWAMY CASE: AADHAR, SECTION-377 AND MORE - RGNUL Student Research Review (RSRR)|date=2018-11-16|website=RGNUL  Student Research  Review (RSRR)|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indconlawphil.wordpress.com/2017/08/31/the-supreme-courts-right-to-privacy-judgment-v-privacy-and-decisional-autonomy/|title=The Supreme Court\u2019s Right to Privacy Judgment \u2013 V: Privacy and Decisional Autonomy|last=Bhatia|first=Gautam|date=2017-08-31|website=Indian Constitutional Law and Philosophy|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalfreedomofexpression.columbia.edu/cases/puttaswamy-v-india/|title=Puttaswamy v. India|website=Global Freedom of Expression|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> in the judgment of the Supreme Court declaring Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code unconstitutional.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article24880700.ece/binary/Sec377judgment.pdf|title=Section 377 Judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> His opinion is also known for expressly overruling the ADM Jabalpur v. Shiv Kant Shukla (Habeas Corpus) case in which the lead opinion was written by the father of Justice Chandrachud - former Chief Justice of India [[V. Y. Chandrachud]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livelaw.in/rare-moment-history-justice-d-y-chandrachud-overrules-fathers-judgment-adm-jabalpur-case/|title=A Rare Moment In History: Justice D.Y.Chandrachud Overrules His Father\u2019s Judgment In ADM Jabalpur Case|last=Network|first=LiveLaw News|date=2017-08-24|website=www.livelaw.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Abraham|first=Rohan|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/chandrachud-vs-chandrachud-sc-judge-confident-his-father-would-have-concurred-on-adm-jabalpur-verdict/articleshow/71736077.cms?from=mdr|title=Chandrachud vs Chandrachud: SC judge confident his father would have concurred on ADM Jabalpur verdict|date=2019-10-24|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Free Speech ===\nJustice Chandrachud has termed dissent as \u201cthe safety valve of democracy\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Politics/SiXRDqBThdK92lfR0CRyEP/Dissent-is-the-safety-valve-of-democracy-says-SC.html|title=Dissent is the safety valve of democracy, says SC|last=Ghadyalpatil|first=Shaswati Das ,Abhiram|date=2018-08-29|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/dissent-is-the-safety-valve-of-a-democracy-justice-chandrachud/story-1vOft3QfRvszjGuBBWSuLI.html|title=\u2018Dissent is the safety valve of a democracy\u2019: Justice Chandrachud|date=2020-02-15|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/justice-d-y-chandrachud-caa-protest-democracy-anti-national-6269831/|title=Dissent is \u2018safety valve\u2019 of democracy: Justice Chandrachud|date=2020-02-15|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and has authored judgments upholding the right to the freedom of speech in numerous cases. In Indibility Creative Pvt Ltd v State of West Bengal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2019/8409/8409_2019_Judgement_11-Apr-2019.pdf|title=Indibility Creative Pvt Ltd Judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, he authored a judgment which imposed a fine on the State of West Bengal and granted remedial compensation for disallowing the screening of the political satire ''Bhobishyoter Bhoot'' through extra-constitutional measures. The Court had, by an interim order, directed that there must be no bar on the screening of the movie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://punemirror.indiatimes.com/news/india/ensure-screening-of-anik-duttas-bhobishyoter-bhoot-supreme-court-to-west-bengal-govt/articleshow/68430662.cms|title=Ensure screening of Anik Dutta's Bhobishyoter Bhoot: Supreme Court to West Bengal govt|last=Nag|first=Jayatri NagJayatri|last2=Mar 15|first2=Mumbai Mirror {{!}} Updated:|website=Pune Mirror|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20|last3=2019|last4=Ist|first4=20:33}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/supreme-court-political-class-puzzle-on-bhobishyoter-bhoot/cid/1688003|title=Supreme Court political-class puzzle on Bhobishyoter Bhoot|website=www.telegraphindia.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In the final judgment, Justice Chandrachud held that even if there was any apprehension of public discontent, police protection must be provided instead of prohibiting the display of the movie. The judgment is noteworthy<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://indconlawphil.wordpress.com/2019/04/14/making-the-path-by-walking-the-supreme-courts-film-censorship-judgment/|title=Making the Path by Walking: The Supreme Court\u2019s Film Censorship Judgment|last=Bhatia|first=Gautam|date=2019-04-14|website=Indian Constitutional Law and Philosophy|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> for its recognition of the positive duty on the State to protect the freedom of speech and expression. He held that:<blockquote>Free speech cannot be gagged for fear of the mob\u2026Political freedoms impose a restraining influence on the state by carving out an area in which the state shall not interfere. Hence, these freedoms are perceived to impose obligations of restraint on the state. But, apart from imposing \u2018negative\u2019 restraints on the state these freedoms impose a positive mandate as well. In its capacity as a public authority enforcing the rule of law, the state must ensure that conditions in which these freedoms flourish are maintained. In the space reserved for the free exercise of speech and expression, the state cannot look askance when organized interests threaten the existence of freedom. The state is duty bound to ensure the prevalence of conditions in which of those freedoms can be exercised. The instruments of the state must be utilized to effectuate the exercise of freedom.</blockquote>The judgment was widely reported<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/judiciary/how-sc-defended-freedom-of-speech-by-pulling-up-mamata-govt-for-blocking-satirical-film/220358/|title=How SC defended freedom of speech by pulling up Mamata govt for blocking satirical film|last=Jain|first=Ritika|date=2019-04-11|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thelogicalindian.com/news/sc-fines-wb-govt/|title=Free Speech Cannot Be Gagged': SC Fines Mamata Govt Rs 20 Lakh For 'Virtual Ban' On Movie|last=Indian|first=The Logical|date=2019-04-12|website=thelogicalindian.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/pay-rs-20-lakh-to-producer-supreme-court-tells-mamata-government/story-QejpUcjZpWlYFJcTrc8SdP.html|title=Pay Rs 20 lakh to producer, Supreme Court tells Mamata government|date=2019-04-12|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/india-news-sc-imposes-rs-20-lakh-fine-on-mamata-govt-for-ban-on-film-bhobishyoter-bhoot/328517|title=Supreme Court Imposes Rs 20 Lakh Fine On Mamata Govt For 'Virtual Ban' On Film 'Bhobishyoter Bhoot'|website=https://www.outlookindia.com/|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> for preventing the censorship of free speech and limiting its exceptions strictly to the grounds mentioned in Article 19(2) of the Constitution. \n\nIn Romila Thapar & Ors. v. Union of India & Ors, Justice Chandrachud dissented with the majority which refused to constitute a Special Investigation Team to probe the case concerning the arrest of five activists in connection with the [[2018 Bhima Koregaon violence]] and held that in light of the particular circumstances of the case, the constitution of a Special Investigation Team was necessary to ensure a fair and impartial investigation.\n\n=== Gender Justice ===\n\n==== Sabarimala verdict ====\nJustice Chandrachud has authored several judgments on gender justice that call for a \u2018change in mindsets\u2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.barandbench.com/news/litigation/change-mindset-to-bring-true-equality-in-army-sc-holds-permanent-commission-should-be-available-to-all-women-officers|title=Change mindset to bring true equality in Army: SC holds Permanent Commission should be available to all women officers|last=Emmanuel|first=Meera|website=Bar and Bench - Indian Legal news|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> as well as affirm the equal entitlements of women under the Constitution. In Indian Young Lawyers Association v. State of Kerala<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2006/18956/18956_2006_Judgement_28-Sep-2018.pdf|title=Sabarimala judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, he authored a concurring judgment holding that the practice of prohibiting women of menstruating age from entering the [[Sabarimala]] temple was discriminatory and violated the fundamental rights of women. In his judgment, he highlighted that \u201cthe individual right to the freedom of religion was not intended to prevail over but was subject to the overriding constitutional postulates of equality, liberty and personal freedoms recognised in the other provisions of Part III.\u201d<ref name=\":3\" /> He held that:<blockquote>The Court must lean against granting constitutional protection to a claim which derogates from the dignity of women as equal holders of rights and protections\u2026 Does the Constitution permit this as basis to exclude women from worship? Does the fact that a woman has a physiological feature \u2013 of being in a menstruating age \u2013 entitle anybody or a group to subject her to exclusion from religious worship? The physiological features of a woman have no significance to her equal entitlements under the Constitution\u2026 To exclude women is derogatory to an equal citizenship.</blockquote>His opinion was widely acknowledged<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indconlawphil.wordpress.com/2018/09/29/the-sabarimala-judgment-iii-justice-chandrachud-and-radical-equality/|title=The Sabarimala Judgment \u2013 III: Justice Chandrachud and Radical Equality|last=Bhatia|first=Gautam|date=2018-09-29|website=Indian Constitutional Law and Philosophy|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Rajagopal|first=Krishnadas|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/sabarimala-verdict-justice-chandrachud-calls-to-balance-group-rights-with-individual-freedoms/article25074121.ece|title=Sabarimala verdict: Justice Chandrachud calls to balance group rights with individual freedoms|date=2018-09-28|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> for recognizing that denying entry into temples to women on the basis of physiology amounted to a constitutionally prohibited practice of untouchability under Article 17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/sabarimala-temple-ban-because-of-menstruation-utterly-unconstitutional-supreme-court-1923609|title=Sabarimala Ban \"A Form Of Untouchability\", Says Justice Chandrachud|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forwardpress.in/2018/10/sabarimala-ayyappa-temple-justice-chandrachud-eng/|title=Exclusion of women from Sabarimala amounts to untouchability: Justice Chandrachud|last=\u091d\u093e|first=Ashok Jha \u0905\u0936\u094b\u0915|date=2018-10-06|website=Forward Press|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/purification-ritual-at-sabarimala-appears-to-violate-ban-on-untouchability-undermines-dy-chandrachuds-observations-in-28-sept-sc-verdict-5826081.html|title='Purification' ritual at Sabarimala appears to violate ban on untouchability, undermines DY Chandrachud's observations in 28 Sept SC verdict|website=Firstpost|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> He stated that \u201cthe social exclusion of women, based on menstrual status, is a form of untouchability, which is contrary to constitutional values. Notions of \u2018purity\u2019 and \u2018pollution\u2019, which stigmatise individuals, have no place in a constitutional order.\u201d<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nFollowing protests against the judgment in the State of Kerala<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-46744142|title=India state paralysed amid temple protest|date=2019-01-03|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/culture/2019/01/sabarimala-temple-india-kerala-protests/|title=Women visited this sacred temple. Then violent protests broke out. Why?|date=2019-01-08|website=Culture|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/sabarimala-unrest-kerala-activist-dies-in-clash-hartal-today-1422363-2019-01-03|title=Sabarimala protests: Activist succumbs to injuries, Kerala on edge after 2 women enter temple|last=ThiruvananthapuramJanuary 3|first=India Today Web Desk|last2=January 3|first2=2019UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20|last3=Ist|first3=2019 11:07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/protests-in-kerala-after-two-women-enter-sabarimala-temple/articleshow/67347043.cms?from=mdr|title=Protests in Kerala as 2 women enter Sabarimala temple, state-wide shutdown tomorrow|date=2019-01-02|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/01/tens-thousands-protest-india-sabarimala-temple-190101140533525.html|title=Tens of thousands protest in India over Sabarimala temple|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>, a five judge Bench of the Indian Supreme Court, while hearing a review petition against the judgment in November 2019, decided to refer the matter to a larger Bench. Justice Chandrachud and Justice Nariman (who were both part of the original Bench that passed the majority judgment) dissented<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/issues-not-before-this-court-2-who-differ-6120274/|title=Sabarimala dissenting view: What Justices Nariman, Chandrachud said|date=2019-11-15|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/to-review-or-not-is-only-narrow-question-rest-later-the-2-in-3-2-6120506/|title=Sabarimala: To review or not is only narrow question, rest later: The 2 in 3-2|date=2019-11-15|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and held that the parameters for the exercise of the review jurisdiction of the Court had not been met.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/sabarimala-let-big-bench-decide-larger-issues-essential-religious-practices-supreme-court-6120529/|title=Sabarimala review plea: Let big bench decide larger issues, essential religious practices, rules SC|date=2019-11-15|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==== Adultery ====\nIn Joseph Shine v Union of India<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2017/32550/32550_2017_Judgement_27-Sep-2018.pdf|title=Joseph Shine Judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> he authored a concurring judgment declaring the provision of the Indian Penal Code which concerned the [[adultery law in India]] unconstitutional. Emphasizing the constitutional commitment to equality and dignity, he held that:<blockquote>The creation of a just, egalitarian society is a process. It often involves the questioning and obliteration of parochial social mores which are antithetical to constitutional morality\u2026The ability to make choices within marriage and on every aspect concerning it is a facet of human liberty and dignity which the Constitution protects\u2026 Implicit in seeking to privilege the fidelity of women in a marriage, is the assumption that a woman contracts away her sexual agency when entering a marriage. That a woman, by marriage, consents in advance to sexual relations with her husband or to refrain from sexual relations outside marriage without the permission of her husband is offensive to liberty and dignity. Such a notion has no place in the constitutional order. Sexual autonomy constitutes an inviolable core of the dignity of every individual.<ref name=\":4\" /></blockquote>His concurring opinion was noticed for its emphasis on the sexual autonomy of women even within the bounds of a marital relationship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.barandbench.com/news/marital-rape-debate-justice-dy-chandrachud-right-say-no-marriage|title=Marital Rape Debate: Justice DY Chandrachud on Right to say \u201cno\u201d after Marriage|last=Krishnan|first=Murali|website=Bar and Bench - Indian Legal news|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/husband-not-the-master-of-his-wife-supreme-court-scraps-150-year-old-law-made-adultery-crime/story/282918.html|title='Husband not the master of his wife': Supreme Court scraps 150-year-old law that made adultery a crime|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> He held that:<blockquote>\u2026. in adjudicating on the rights of women, the Court is not taking on a paternalistic role and \u201cgranting\u201d rights. The Court is merely interpreting the text of the Constitution to re-state what is already set in ink \u2014 women are equal citizens of this nation, entitled to the protections of the Constitution. Any legislation which results in the denial of these Constitutional guarantees to women, cannot pass the test of Constitutionality.<ref name=\":4\" /></blockquote>It is reported<ref>{{Cite news|last=India|first=Press Trust of|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/married-women-have-sexual-autonomy-like-right-to-say-no-sc-118080201433_1.html|title=Married women have sexual autonomy like right to say 'no': SC|date=2018-08-02|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/supreme-court-signal-on-marital-rape-consent-sexual-autonomy-in-marriage-are-key-values-5377501/|title=Supreme Court signal on marital rape: Consent, sexual autonomy in marriage are key values|date=2018-09-28|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> that the above observations have a significant bearing on the law employed for the [[restitution of conjugal rights]] as well as the exception carved out in law from criminalizing marital rape. Interestingly, this case was the second case where Justice Chandrachud overruled<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/adultery-law-justice-dy-chandrachud-overturns-another-judgment-by-father-yv-chandrachud-1350758-2018-09-27|title=Adultery law: Justice DY Chandrachud overturns another judgment by his father|last=DelhiSeptember 27|first=Prabhash K. Dutta New|last2=September 27|first2=2018UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20|last3=Ist|first3=2018 23:37}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/supreme-court-verdict-on-adultery-justice-dy-chandrachud-does-it-again-overrules-fathers-judgment-5277261.html|title=Supreme Court verdict on adultery: Justice DY Chandrachud does it again, overrules father's judgment|website=Firstpost|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-in/news/newsindia/adultery-law-justice-dy-chandrachud-overturns-another-judgment-by-his-father/ar-BBNBY9c|title=Adultery law: Justice DY Chandrachud overturns another judgment by his father|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2018/sep/28/adultery-verdict-justice-chandrachud-overrules-his-father-y-v-chandrachuds-ruling-1878105.html|title=Adultery verdict: Justice Chandrachud overrules his father Y V Chandrachud's ruling|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livelaw.in/justice-chandrachud-does-it-again-overrules-fathers-33-year-old-judgment-on-adultery-law/|title=Justice Chandrachud Does It Again, Overrules His Father's 33 Year Old Judgment On Adultery Law [Read Judgment]|last=Sebastian|first=Manu|date=2018-09-27|website=www.livelaw.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> a decision of his father, former Chief Justice of India [[V. Y. Chandrachud]].\n\n==== Armed Forces ====\n\n===== Army =====\nIn 2020, he authored two landmark decisions in the realm of gender justice and the armed forces of the country. In The Secretary, Ministry of Defence v Babita Puniya<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2010/20695/20695_2010_8_1501_20635_Judgement_17-Feb-2020.pdf|title=Babita Puniya judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> he directing the government to consider all woman officers in the Army appointed on Short Service Commissions for the grant of Permanent Commissions on an equal basis with their male counterparts. The Union Government had contended that \u201cwomen are not employed on duties which are hazardous in nature unlike their male counterparts in the same Arm/Service.\u201d<ref name=\":5\" /> It was also contended that the \u201cinherent physiological differences between men and women preclude equal physical performances resulting in lower physical standards.\u201d<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn a section titled \u2018Stereotypes and women in the Armed Forces\u2019, he emphasized on the need for a change in mindsets and came down heavily on the submissions of the Union Government and held that:<blockquote>The submissions advanced\u2026are based on sex stereotypes premised on assumptions about socially ascribed roles of gender which discriminate against women. Underlying the statement that it is a \u201cgreater challenge\u201d for women officers to meet the hazards of service \u201cowing to their prolonged absence during pregnancy, motherhood and domestic obligations towards their children and families\u201d is a strong stereotype which assumes that domestic obligations rest solely on women. Reliance on the \u201cinherent physiological differences between men and women\u201d rests in a deeply entrenched stereotypical and constitutionally flawed notion that women are the \u201cweaker\u201d sex and may not undertake tasks that are \u201ctoo arduous\u201d for them. Arguments founded on the physical strengths and weaknesses of men and women and on assumptions about women in the social context of marriage and family do not constitute a constitutionally valid basis for denying equal opportunity to women officers\u2026If society holds strong beliefs about gender roles \u2013 that men are socially dominant, physically powerful and the breadwinners of the family and that women are weak and physically submissive, and primarily caretakers confined to a domestic atmosphere \u2013 it is unlikely that there would be a change in mindsets.<ref name=\":5\" /></blockquote>The judgment was reported internationally<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51528141|title=India army takes 'great leap' towards equality|date=2020-02-17|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-india-women-military-idUSKBN20B1X4|title=India's top court orders equal roles for women in army|date=2020-02-17|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/sexism-in-indian-army-top-court-ruling-shatters-glass-ceiling-for-women-officers/a-52419901|title=Sexism in Indian army: Top court ruling shatters glass ceiling for women officers {{!}} DW {{!}} 18.02.2020|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche|website=DW.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> as well as in national media as a \u201clandmark verdict ending gender bias\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/feb/17/sc-directs-centre-to-grant-permanent-commission-to-women-officers-in-army-2104553.html|title=SC directs Centre to grant permanent commission to women army officers in landmark verdict ending gender bias|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Feb 2020|first=Times Now {{!}} 17|title=SC directs permanent commission to women officers in armed forces|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/sc-directs-permanent-commission-to-women-officers-in-armed-forces/videoshow/74170629.cms|access-date=2020-04-20|last2=Ist|first2=12:25 Pm}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/defence/women-to-get-permanent-commission-in-indian-army-heres-everything-about-the-scs-historic-judgement/1870295/|title=Women to get permanent commission in Indian Army! Here\u2019s everything about the SC\u2019s historic judgement|date=2020-02-17|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/theprint-essential/women-arent-adjuncts-what-sc-said-while-granting-permanent-commission-to-women-in-army/366907/|title='Women aren't adjuncts' \u2014 what SC said while granting permanent commission to women in Army|last=M|first=Apoorva|last2=hani|date=2020-02-17|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> which is \u201cagainst deeply embedded patriarchal mindsets and strong institutional biases.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/editorials/women-in-indian-army-supreme-court-verdict-6274777/|title=In her own right|date=2020-02-19|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> At the International Judicial Conference hosted by India on the \u2018Judiciary and the Changing World\u2019, which saw the participation of Chief Justices and judges from over 23 countries, the President of India welcomed the judgment and commended it for its \u201cprogressive social transformation\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://164.100.117.97/WriteReadData/userfiles/International%20Judicial%20Conference23022019.pdf|title=Speech of the President at the IJC 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n===== Navy =====\nA short time thereafter, he authored the judgment in Union of India v Ld. Cdr. Annie Nagaraja<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2015/35837/35837_2015_3_1502_21539_Judgement_17-Mar-2020.pdf|title=Annie Nagaraja Judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> wherein the Court directed a similar relief to be granted to women sailors in the Indian Navy. The Court noted the submission of the Union Government that \u201ccertain avenues such as sea-sailing duties are ill-suited for women officers as there is no return to the base\u201d and that \u201cNavy ships of today are not structured nor have the infrastructure to accommodate women sailors alongside men sailors\u201d and rejected these submissions as \u201cillusory and without any foundation\u201d.<ref name=\":6\" /> He held that:<blockquote>A hundred and one excuses are no answer to the constitutional entitlement to dignity, which attaches to every individual irrespective of gender, to fair and equal conditions of work and to a level playing field. A level playing field ensures that women have the opportunity to overcome their histories of discrimination with the surest of responses based on their competence, ability and performance.<ref name=\":6\" /></blockquote>The judgment received similar international attention<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.laht.com/article.asp?ArticleId=2490469&CategoryId=12395|title=Latin American Herald Tribune - \u2018End Gender Stereotypes\u2019: Indian Court Rules in Favor of Women Navy Officers|website=www.laht.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and was widely reported upon in national media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/after-army-supreme-court-grants-permanent-commission-to-women-officers-in-navy/articleshow/74667440.cms?from=mdr|title=After Army, Supreme Court grants permanent commission to women officers in Navy|date=2020-03-17|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/women-sail-with-same-efficiency-sc-says-yes-to-permanent-commission-for-women-in-navy/382258/|title=\u2018Women sail with same efficiency\u2019 \u2014 SC says yes to permanent commission for women in Navy|last=Roy|first=Debayan|date=2020-03-17|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/sc-grants-permanent-commission-to-women-in-indian-navy-11584423945637.html|title=SC rules in favour of permanent commission for women officers in Navy|last=Bindra|first=Japnam|date=2020-03-17|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/after-army-supreme-court-grants-permanent-commission-to-women-officers-in-navy/articleshow/74667440.cms|title=After Army, Supreme Court grants permanent commission to women officers in Navy|date=2020-03-17|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hwnews.in/uncategorized/after-army-way-for-permanent-commission-to-women-in-navy-cleared-by-sc/127932|title=After Army, Way For Permanent Commission To Women In Navy Cleared by SC|last=Desk|first=News|date=2020-03-19|website=HW English|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/defence/boost-for-women-in-indian-navy-supreme-court-allows-permanent-commission-details/1900480/|title=Boost for women in Indian Navy! Supreme Court allows permanent commission; details|date=2020-03-17|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/mar/17/first-army-now-navy-supreme-court-nods-yes-to-permanent-commission-for-women--2117769.html|title=First Army, now Navy: Supreme Court nods yes to permanent commission for women|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestatesman.com/india/sail-efficiently-males-sc-grants-permanent-commission-women-officers-navy-1502866895.html|title='Can sail as efficiently as males': SC grants permanent commission to women officers in Navy|date=2020-03-17|website=The Statesman|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/women-equal-to-men-sc-grants-women-permanent-commission-in-navy/1771246|title=''Women equal to men'': SC grants women permanent commission in Navy|website=https://www.outlookindia.com/|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==== Sexual Harassment at the workplace ====\nRecently, he authored a judgment which affirmed affirming that sexual harassment at the workplace violates the fundamental rights of women guaranteed under the Indian Constitution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/sexual-harassment-at-workplace-is-affront-to-rights-of-woman-sc/1757982|title=Sexual harassment at workplace is affront to rights of woman: SC|website=https://www.outlookindia.com/|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> The verdict was based on a complaint made by a senior officer of the Punjab and Sind Bank that she was transferred out from Indore to Jabalpur because she had complained about irregularities and corruption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/sexual-harassment-affront-to-rights-of-woman-employee-supreme-court-812784.html|title=Sexual harassment affront to rights of woman employee: Supreme Court|date=2020-03-11|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> The woman, a chief manager and Scale IV officer, said she was also allegedly sexually harassed by her senior officer. He held that:<blockquote>Sexual harassment at the workplace is an affront to the fundamental rights of a woman to equality under Articles 14 and 15 and her right to live with dignity under Article 21 of the Constitution as well as her right to practice any profession or to carry on any occupation, trade or business\u2026 There can be no manner of doubt that the respondent (woman officer) has been victimized. This is symptomatic of a carrot and sticks policy adopted to suborn the dignity of a woman who is aggrieved by unfair treatment at her workplace. The law cannot countenance this. The order of transfer was an act of unfair treatment and is vitiated by malafides.</blockquote>He directed the bank to send the woman employee back to the Indore branch and held that the bank may pass any other order only after she has completed a tenure of one year at the Indore branch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/latest/955827/sexual-harassment-at-workplace-violates-womens-fundamental-rights-supreme-court|title=Sexual harassment at workplace violates women\u2019s fundamental rights: Supreme Court|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Environment ===\nOne of Justice Chandrachud\u2019s significant<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/opinion/in-perspective/failed-by-ngt-saved-by-sc-731335.html|title=Failed by NGT, saved by SC|date=2019-04-29|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=IANS|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/goa-activists-opposition-welcome-sc-order-on-airport-119032901261_1.html|title=Goa activists, Opposition welcome SC order on airport|date=2019-03-29|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.civilsocietyonline.com/environment/rainbow-warriors-in-goa-get-new-airport-eia-annulled/|title=Rainbow Warriors in Goa get new airport EIA annulled - Civil Society Magazine|website=www.civilsocietyonline.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> opinions in the sphere of environmental law is his judgment in Hanuman Laxman Aroskar v Union of India<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2018/43379/43379_2018_Judgement_29-Mar-2019.pdf|title=Mopa, Goa judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. A challenge was brought before the Supreme Court against the order of the National Green Tribunal upholding the grant of an Environmental Clearance to a proposed greenfield international airport at Mopa in Goa. A myriad of contentions were urged by the appellants questioning the grant of the clearance, which included the failure to make disclosures on forests and Ecologically Sensitive Zones as well as a faulty appraisal process and the use of erroneous sampling points. The Court observed the numerous deficiencies in the process leading to the grant of the clearance and directed that a rapid EIA be conducted afresh<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scconline.com/blog/post/2019/03/30/environmental-clearance-for-development-of-airport-at-mopa-goa-to-be-revisited/|title=Environmental Clearance for development of Airport at Mopa, Goa to be revisited|last=Bhardwaj|first=Prachi|date=2019-03-29|website=SCC Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/law-and-policy/sc-suspends-environmental-clearance-to-mopa-airport-asks-eac-to-revisit-decision|title=Supreme Court Suspends Environmental Clearance Granted To Goa\u2019s Mopa Airport|website=BloombergQuint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> by the project proponent. The Court highlighted that compliance with the core governing notification is mandatory in the following terms:<blockquote>The 2006 notification represents an independent code with the avowed objective of balancing the development agenda with the protection of the environment. An applicant cannot claim an EC, under the 2006 notification, based on substantial or proportionate compliance with the terms stipulated in the notification. The terms of the notification lay down strict standards that must be complied with by an applicant seeking an EC for a proposed project. The burden of establishing environmental compliance rests on a project proponent who intends to bring about a change in the existing state of the environment\u2026 There can be no gambles with the environment: a \u2018heads I win, tails you lose\u2019 approach is simply unacceptable; unacceptable if we are to preserve environmental governance under the rule of law.<ref name=\":7\" /></blockquote>The judgment has expounded on the concept of the \u2018environmental rule of law\u2019 as a groundwork for the protection of the environment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/goa-turbulence-throws-light-on-mega-projects-1556208292034.html|title=Goa turbulence throws light on mega projects|date=2019-04-25|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The judgment was also welcomed by the United Nations Environment Program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iamrenew.com/environment/un-lauds-sc-decision-to-suspend-construction-of-controversial-goa-airport/|title=UN Lauds SC Decision To Suspend Construction of Goa Airport|date=2019-04-02|website=Renewable Energy and Environmental Sustainability in India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> In a separate section titled the \u2018Environmental Rule of Law\u2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://epaper.timesgroup.com/Olive/ODN/TimesOfIndia/shared/ShowArticle.aspx?doc=TOIM/2019/03/31&entity=Ar00907&sk=8A6A3A2D&mode=text#|title=SC quotes \u2018environmental rule of law\u2019, stalls Goa\u2019s Mopa airport - The Times Of India - Mumbai, 3/31/2019|website=epaper.timesgroup.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> the Court drew from vast literature<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/goa-turbulence-throws-light-on-mega-projects-1556208292034.html|title=Goa turbulence throws light on mega projects|date=2019-04-25|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> on environmental law which included the UN Sustainable Development Goals and the work of Amartya Sen and Dhvani Mehta to draw a link between the protection of the environment and the right to life under Article 21 of the Indian Constitution.\n\n\nIn Bangalore Development Authority v Mr Sudhakar Hegde,<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2019/8100/8100_2019_3_1503_21539_Judgement_17-Mar-2020.pdf|title=BDA judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> he authored a judgment directing the appellant to conduct a rapid EIA as a result of the numerous deficiencies in the process leading upto the grant of Environmental Clearance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/state/get-fresh-environmental-impact-study-for-prr-supreme-court-to-karnataka-govt-814825.html|title=Get fresh environmental impact study for PRR: Supreme Court to Karnataka govt|date=2020-03-18|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The Court noted the \u201cpatent contradiction\u201d in disclosing the existence of forest land to be diverted for the project connecting Tumkur Road to Hosur Road.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2020/mar/18/apex-court-raps-bda-over-prr-seeks-new-eco-study-2118183.html|title=Apex court raps BDA over PRR, seeks new eco-study|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/city/top-bengaluru-stories/take-fresh-environmental-clearance-for-8-lane-project-in-bengaluru-sc-to-bda-814629.html|title=Take fresh environmental clearance for 8-lane project in Bengaluru: SC to BDA|date=2020-03-17|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> In a section titled \u2018Courts and the Environment\u2019, he highlighted the importance of a broad-based approach to the protection of the environment in the following terms:<blockquote>The protection of the environment is premised not only on the active role of courts, but also on robust institutional frameworks within which every stakeholder complies with its duty to ensure sustainable development. A framework of environmental governance committed to the rule of law requires a regime which has effective, accountable and transparent institutions. Equally important is responsive, inclusive, participatory and representative decision making. Environmental governance is founded on the rule of law and emerges from the values of our Constitution. Where the health of the environment is key to preserving the right to life as a constitutionally recognized value under Article 21 of the Constitution, proper structures for environmental decision making find expression in the guarantee against arbitrary action and the affirmative duty of fair treatment under Article 14 of the Constitution.<ref name=\":8\" /></blockquote>Justice Chandrachud has also authored a judgment on the validity of grating ''ex post facto'' Environmental Clearances in Alembic Pharmaceuticals Ltd v Rohit Prajapati.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2016/2562/2562_2016_0_1501_21582_Judgement_01-Apr-2020.pdf|title=Alembic Judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The erstwhile Ministry of Environmental and Forests had issued an administrative circular in 2002 envisaging the grant of ''ex post facto'' clearances to those industries that had failed to comply with the mandatory EIA notification of 1994. The ex post facto clearances granted to a group of drug and pharmaceutical companies located in Gujarat were challenged. Justice Chandrachud set aside the administrative circular of 2002 and noted that the concept of ''ex post facto'' ECs derogates from the fundamental principles of the environmental rule of law. He noted that the grant of ''ex post facto'' ECs was contrary to both the precautionary principle as well as the principal of sustainable development.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/sc-penalises-three-pharma-cos-asks-to-pay-fine-of-rs-10-cr-each-820450.html|title=SC penalises three pharma cos, asks to pay fine of Rs 10 Cr each|date=2020-04-02|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Justice Chandrachud noted that all the industries in question had made significant infrastructural investments. In this backdrop, he imposed a fine of Rs 10 crores each for the purpose of restitution and restoration of the environment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lawstreet.co/judiciary/industries-causing-pollution-asked-to-pay-compensation?refuid=ODAzM3w1MC42My4xNjAuMjE3fHNvb2xlZ2FsLmNvbQ==|title=Industries Causing Pollution Asked To Pay Rs. 30 Crore As Compensation For Preservation Of Environment: SC [Read Order]|last=Lawstreet|website=Lawstreet.co|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livelaw.in/environment/ex-post-facto-environmental-clearance-unsustainable-in-law-sc-154678|title='Ex Post Facto' Environmental Clearance Unsustainable In Law : SC [Read Judgment]|last=NETWORK|first=LIVELAW NEWS|date=2020-04-02|website=www.livelaw.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>  He held:<blockquote>Requirements such as conducting a public hearing, screening, scoping and appraisal are components of the decision-making process which ensure that the likely impacts of the industrial activity or the expansion of an existing industrial activity are considered in the decision-making calculus. Allowing for an ex post facto clearance would essentially condone the operation of industrial activities without the grant of an EC. In the absence of an EC, there would be no conditions that would safeguard the environment. Moreover, if the EC was to be ultimately refused, irreparable harm would have been caused to the environment. In either view of the matter, environment law cannot countenance the notion of an ex post facto clearance. This would be contrary to both the precautionary principle as well as the need for sustainable development.<ref name=\":9\" /></blockquote>\n\n== Others ==\nJustice Chandrachud has also been the voice of a strong dissent in notable cases. He wrote a dissenting opinion in the Aadhaar<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremecourtofindia.nic.in/supremecourt/2012/35071/35071_2012_Judgement_26-Sep-2018.pdf|title=Aadhaar}}</ref> case, where the majority upheld the constitutional validity of the largest biometric identity project in the world. Justice Chandrachud held the project to be unconstitutional and violative of fundamental rights. In Jindal Stainless Ltd. v. State of Haryana,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/jonew/judis/44300.pdf|title=Entry Tax}}</ref> a 9-judge Bench decision on the constitutional validity of entry tax imposed by states in India, Justice Chandrachud authored a dissenting opinion. He also wrote a dissent in Abhiram Singh v. CD Commachen,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/jonew/judis/44451.pdf|title=Abhiram Singh}}</ref> a case concerning the regulation of election speech, and in Santhini v. Vijaya Venkatesh<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2016/27362/27362_2016_Judgement_09-Oct-2017.pdf|title=Santhini}}</ref> on the question of the validity of video-conferencing in matrimonial and family cases. In Romila Thapar & Ors. v. Union of India & Ors,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2018/32319/32319_2018_Judgement_28-Sep-2018.pdf|title=Romila Thapar}}</ref> Justice Chandrachud dissented with the majority which refused to constitute a Special Investigation Team to probe the case concerning the arrest of five activists in connection with the Bhima Koregoan violence and held that in light of the particular circumstances of the case, the constitution of a Special Investigation Team was necessary to ensure a fair and impartial investigation.\n\nHe has also authored opinions in the decisions of Common Cause v. Union of India<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2005/9123/9123_2005_Judgement_09-Mar-2018.pdf|title=Common Cause}}</ref> legalising passive euthanasia and living wills, the ruling in Govt. of NCT of Delhi v. Union of India & Anr<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremecourtofindia.nic.in/pdf/LU/29357.pdf|title=NCT Delhi}}</ref> on the balance of powers between the Lt. Governor and the Chief Minister in the governance of the National Capital Territory, Kalpana Mehta & Ors. v. Union of India & Ors<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2012/36970/36970_2012_Judgement_09-May-2018.pdf|title=Kalpana Mehta}}</ref> which held that the reliance on Parliamentary Standing Committee Reports by Courts did not constitute a breach of Parliamentary privilege, and in Swapnil Tripathi v. Supreme Court of India,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2017/40426/40426_2017_Judgement_26-Sep-2018.pdf|title=Live-Streaming}}</ref> the judgment which allowed live streaming of Indian court cases. In his judgment regarding the construction of a new airport in Goa and resulting environmental law violations, the Environmental Clearance (EC) granted for the construction of the new airport at Mopa in Goa has been suspended until the Expert Appraisal Committee (EAC) revisits the recommendations made for the grant of an EC. The judgment is significant for developing the jurisprudence on \"environmental rule of law\" and its treatment of ecologically sensitive zones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2018/43379/43379_2018_Judgement_29-Mar-2019.pdf|title=In the Supreme Court of India Civil Appellate Jurisdiction}}</ref> In Indibility Creative Pvt Ltd v State of West Bengal,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2019/8409/8409_2019_Judgement_11-Apr-2019.pdf|title=Indibility Creative v. Govt. of West Bengal}}</ref> he authored a judgment which imposed a fine on the State of West Bengal and granted remedial compensation for not allowing the screening of&nbsp; the political satire ''Bhobishyoter Bhoot'', through extra-constitutional measures. The judgment is also noteworthy for its recognition of the positive duty of the State to protect the freedom of speech and expression. In B.K. Pavitra II v. Union of India,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2018/15655/15655_2018_Judgement_10-May-2019.pdf|title=B.K. Pavitra v. Union of India}}</ref> he authored a landmark judgement which upheld the constitutional validity of the Karnataka Extension of Consequential Seniority to Government Servants Promoted on the Basis of Reservation (to the Posts in the Civil Services of the State) Act 2018 &nbsp;which adopts the principle that consequential seniority is not an additional benefit but a consequence of the promotion which is granted to members of the Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes. The judgment was celebrated for undertaking a critical, nuanced analysis that favoured an inclusive definition of 'efficiency' and consequently 'merit', - one that is consistent with the principle of substantive equality, as opposed to formal equality.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070806180624/http://www.vmslaw.edu/sympo.htm Millennium laws For India Inc.---A symposium]\n* [http://lawcommissionofindia.nic.in/adr_conf/chandrachud3.pdf M E D I A T I O N \u2013 realizing the potential and designing. implementation strategies.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928170649/http://www.humanrightsinitiative.org/jc/papers/jc_2002/judges_papers/chandrachud_final.pdf First South Asian Regional Judicial Colloquium on Access to Justice]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070820184647/http://www.humanrightsinitiative.org/jc/papers/jc_2003/background_papers.htm CHRI: Judicial Colloquia Series on Access to Justice]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070702192624/http://www.interights.org/page.php?dir=News Justiciability of Economic, Social and Cultural Rights in the Pacific\u2014A judicial colloquium and workshop]\n* [http://www.allahabadhighcourt.in/service/judgeDetail.jsp?id=203|High Court of Judicature at Allahabad]\n\n{{Sitting Judges of the Supreme Court of India}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chandrachud, Dhananjaya Y.}}\n[[Category:20th-century Indian judges]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Faculty of Law, University of Delhi alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian solicitors]]\n[[Category:Judges of the Mumbai High Court]]\n[[Category:St. Columba's School, Delhi alumni]]\n[[Category:Chief Justices of the Allahabad High Court]]\n[[Category:Justices of the Supreme Court of India]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian judges]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian judge}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =Hon'ble Dr. Justice\n| name = Dhananjaya Yeshwant Chandrachud\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = File:Justice D.Y. Chandrachud.jpg\n| image_size = 220px\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| office = [[Judge]] of [[Supreme Court of India]]\n| term_start = 13 May 2016\n| term_end = \n| appointer = [[Pranab Mukherjee]]\n| office1 = [[Allahabad High Court#List of Chief Justices|45th]] [[Chief Justice]] of [[Allahabad High Court]]\n| term_start1 = 31 October 2013\n| term_end1 = 12 May 2016<ref name=\"sc\">{{Cite web |url=http://supremecourtofindia.nic.in/chief-justice-judges |title=Supreme Court of India: Chief Justice & Judges |website=supremecourtofindia.nic.in |language=en |access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n| appointer1 = [[Pranab Mukherjee]]\n| predecessor1 = \n| successor1 = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1959|11|11}}<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allahabadhighcourt.in/service/judgeDetail.jsp?id=203|title=Hon'ble Dr. Justice Dhananjaya Yashwant Chandrachud (CJ)|website=www.allahabadhighcourt.in}}</ref>\n| birth_place = \n| alma_mater = [[St. Columba's School, Delhi]]<br />[[University of Delhi]] ([[B.A.|BA]], [[LLB]])<br />[[Harvard University]] ([[LLM]], [[Doctor of Juridical Science|S.J.D.]])\n| children = 2<ref>{{cite news|title=Justice Chandrachud: the man who doesn't mince words|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/justice-chandrachud-the-man-who-doesn-t-mince-words/cid/1670365|publisher=Telegraph India|accessdate=28 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Collegium system needs reconsideration, says former Supreme Court judge AK Sikri|url=https://theprint.in/india/collegium-system-needs-reconsideration-says-former-supreme-court-judge-ak-sikri/358080/|publisher=The Print|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n| nominator = [[T. S. Thakur]]\n| nominator1 = [[P. Sathasivam]]\n| office2 = [[Judge]] of [[Bombay High Court]]\n| termstart2 = 29 March 2000\n| termend2 = 30 October 2013\n| appointer2 = [[Kocheril Raman Narayanan]]\n| nominator2 = [[Adarsh Sein Anand]]\n}}\n\n'''Dhananjaya Yeshwant Chandrachud''' (born 11 November 1959) is currently a [[Judge]] of  [[Supreme Court of India]]. He is former [[Chief Justice]] of the [[Allahabad High Court]] and a former judge of [[Mumbai High Court|Bombay High Court]].<ref name=\"allahabadhighcourt.in\">{{cite web|url=http://allahabadhighcourt.in/service/judgeDetail.jsp?id=203|title=Hon'ble&nbsp;Dr.&nbsp;Justice&nbsp;Dhananjaya Yashwant Chandrachud&nbsp;(CJ)|work=allahabadhighcourt.in/indexhigh.html|accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vmslaw.edu/sympo.htm|title=Millennium Laws For India Inc.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070806180624/http://www.vmslaw.edu/sympo.htm|archivedate=6 August 2007|url-status=dead|accessdate=23 July 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lawcommissionofindia.nic.in/adr_conf/chandrachud3.pdf |title=Mediiation \u2013 realizing the potential and designin implementation strategies |author=Dr. Hon'ble Justice Shananjaya Y. Chandrachud |website=Lawcommissionofindia.nic.in |accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education==\nChandrachud was born on 11 November 1959.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> His father [[Yeshwant Vishnu Chandrachud]] was the longest serving [[Chief Justice of India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/justice-chandrachud-keeps-running-into-fathers-rulings/articleshow/65250527.cms|title=Justice Chandrachud keeps running into father's rulings}}</ref> His mother Prabha was a classical musician. After attending [[Cathedral and John Connon School]], [[Mumbai]] and [[St. Columba's School, Delhi]], Chandrachud graduated with honours in Economics and Mathematics from [[St. Stephen's College, Delhi|St. Stephen's College]], [[New Delhi]] in 1979.<ref>{{cite web | title =Dhananjaya Y. Chandrachud Dr. Justice | work =Achievers | publisher =Old Columbans' Association | url =http://www.oldcolumban.net/achievers.html | accessdate =9 April 2012 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120226125705/http://www.oldcolumban.net/achievers.html | archivedate =26 February 2012 | df =dmy-all }}</ref> He then obtained his [[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]] degree from [[Delhi University]] in 1982, followed by an [[Master of Laws|LL.M.]] degree from [[Harvard University]] in 1983. At Harvard, he studied on the prestigious Inlaks Scholarship, and received the Joseph H Beale prize.<ref name=\"inlaks\">{{Cite web |url=http://inlaksfoundation.org/Alumni.aspx?sort=old&Type=A&SortAlpha=D |title=Inlaks Shivdasani Foundation: Alumni |date=2010 |website=inlaksfoundation.org |access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref> He went on to receive his Doctorate of Juridical Sciences (S.J.D.), from [[Harvard University]] in 1986.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-10-31/allahabad/43559442_1_chief-justice-bombay-high-court-oath |title=Harvard alumni Hon'ble DY Chandrachud to take oath as Hon'ble chief justice of high court |work=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref> His doctoral thesis was on Affirmative Action; it considered the law in a comparative framework.<ref name=\"hawaii.edu\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hawaii.edu/news/2018/05/31/chandrachud-global-social-justice-lecture/|title=India supreme court justice offers public lecture on global social justice|last=News|first=U. H.|website=University of Hawai\u02bbi System News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref> He had been conferred with an ''Honoris Causa'' [[Legum Doctor|LL.D]]. by [[University of Lucknow|Lucknow University]] in 2015.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/pdf/AnnualReports/Supreme_High_Court_AR_English_2018-19.pdf|title=Indian Judiciary : Annual Report 2018-19|first2=|publisher=The Supreme Court of India, New Delhi|year=2019|isbn=|location=|pages=21}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nChandrachud studied law at Delhi university in 1982 at a time when few jobs were available to young law graduates. He worked for a while, as a junior advocate assisting lawyers and judges, including some memorable briefings that he did for [[Fali Nariman]]. Thereafter he joined [[Harvard law school]]. After graduating Harvard, Chandrachud first worked at [[Sullivan and Cromwell]], a law firm. Chandrachud describes this as \"sheer fluke\" due to the strong pecking order that existed at that time, and a strong bias against Indians and similar developing countries.<ref>{{cite news |title=The evolution of India's legal system - a lecture by Justice D.Y. Chandrachud |publisher=Bloomberg Quint |date=16 December 2017}}</ref> 1986 onwards, national law schools were established in a number of cities in India. He was designated as Senior Advocate by the [[Bombay High Court]] in June 1998. From 1998, he was Additional Solicitor General of India until his appointment as a Judge.\nHe became a judge at the Bombay High Court from 29 March 2000 until his appointment as Chief Justice of the Allahabad High Court. During this time, he was also Director of Maharashtra Judicial Academy. All through, he practised law at the Supreme Court of India and the Bombay High Court. He was Chief Justice of the [[Allahabad High Court]] from 31 October 2013 until appointment to the [[Supreme Court of India]]. He was appointed Judge of the Supreme Court of India on 13 May 2016.<ref name=\"supremecourt\">{{cite web |title=Chief Justice and Judges |url=https://www.supremecourtofindia.nic.in/chief-justice-judges |website=www.supremecourtofindia.nic.in |publisher=Supreme court of India |accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe continues to be a visiting Professor of Comparative Constitutional law at the [[University of Mumbai]] and [[Oklahoma University|Oklahoma University School of Law]], USA. He has delivered lectures at the [[Australian National University]], Deakin University, Melbourne Law School, Harvard Law School, [[Yale Law School]], William S. Richardson School of Law at the University of Hawaii and the [[University of Witwatersrand]], South Africa. He has been a speaker at conferences organised by bodies of the United Nations including [[UNHCR|United Nations High Commission on Human Rights]], International Labour Organisation and United Nations Environmental Program, the World Bank and Asian Development Bank.<ref name=\"sc\"/>\n<ref name=\"allahabadhighcourt.in\" /> He delivered lecture titled \"Global Constitutionalism in the Age of Transnational Judicial Conversations in Human Rights\", organised by Supreme Court of Hawai\u02bbi and the University of Hawai\u02bbi on 6 June 2018.<ref name=\"hawaii.edu\" />\n\n== Notable speeches ==\nJustice Dhananjaya has been a speaker at conferences organised by bodies of the United Nations including United Nations High Commission on Human Rights,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pacific.ohchr.org/final_conclusions.htm|title=OHCHR Regional Office for the Pacific Region|website=pacific.ohchr.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> International Labour Organisation and United Nations Environmental Program, the World Bank and Asian Development Bank. He delivered a lecture titled \u201cGlobal Constitutionalism in the Age of Transnational Judicial Conversations in Human Rights\u201d, organised by Supreme Court of Hawai\u2019i and the University of Hawai\u2019i on 6 June 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hawaii.edu/news/2018/05/31/chandrachud-global-social-justice-lecture/|title=India supreme court justice offers public lecture on global social justice {{!}} University of Hawai\u02bbi System News|last=News|first=U. H.|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> He has delivered numerous speeches in India at premier law institutions as well as events organized by civil society. His most recent speeches include: \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Speeches\n!Date\n!Topic\n!Location\n|-\n|September 2018\n|Rule of Law in a Constitutional Democracy<ref>{{Citation|title=19th Annual Bodh Raj Sawhny Memorial Oration 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YVvRr0ZzRPM|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|19th Annual Bodh Raj Sawhney Memorial, NLUD, Delhi<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nludelhi.ac.in/UploadedImages/a47c94e1-8cd4-48de-81ba-be103bc976a3.pdf|title=NLUD invite|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n|December 2018\n|Law and Storytelling<ref>{{Citation|title=Justice D Y Chandrachud|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pAKZ_IlKeJI|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|Increasing Diversity by Increasing Access (IDIA), Delhi\n|-\n|December 2018\n|Why the Constitution matters<ref>{{Citation|title=Lecture by Hon'ble Justice Dr. D. Y. Chandrachud, on Why Constitution Matters|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vr1Dc_-ZKbQ|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|[[Bombay High Court]]\n|-\n|February 2019\n|Law, Culture and Identity\n|[[Kala Ghoda Arts Festival]], Bombay<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kalaghodaassociation.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Kgaf2019-Booklet-07-02-2019.pdf|title=2019 Invite - Arts Festival|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n|March 2019\n|A Borrowed Constitution: A fact or a myth?<ref>{{Citation|title=\"A Borrowed Constitution: Fact Or Myth\" {{!}} Nani Palkhiwala Lecture By Justice DY Chandrachud {{!}} Part 1|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mNKeSJ6aOKk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|Annual Nani Palkhiwala Lecture, Delhi<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/constitution-contemplated-strong-centre-for-preserving-stability-of-india-chandrachud/1505760|title=Constitution contemplated strong Centre for preserving stability of India: Chandrachud|website=https://www.outlookindia.com/|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|-\n|April 2019\n|Green Law Lecture<ref>{{Citation|title=Green Law Lecture by Hon'ble Justice Dr D.Y. Chandrachud|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oNrcNu7jufY|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|[[O. P. Jindal Global University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jgu.edu.in/blog/2019/03/27/jindal-global-university-launches-environmental-law-course-one-year-masters-programme-in-collaboration-with-wwf-india/|title=Jindal Global University Launches Environmental Law Course: One year Masters Programme in Collaboration with WWF-India|last=JGUAdmin|date=2019-03-27|website=The Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|-\n|August 2019\n|Imagining Freedom Through Art<ref>{{Citation|title=Imagining Freedom Through Art with Justice Dhanjaya Chandrachud|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j4bIXgJI-Xc|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|Literature Live, Annual Independence Day Lecture, Bombay<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gupte|first=Masoom|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/lit-live-i-day-lecture-justice-chandrachud-takes-the-mic-will-encourage-people-to-imagine-freedom-via-art/articleshow/70701299.cms|title=Lit Live I-Day Lecture: Justice Chandrachud takes the mic, will encourage people to imagine freedom via art|date=2019-08-16|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n|}\nMore recently, in December 2019, he delivered a speech titled \u2018Adding Nuance to Human Rights Discourse\u2019<ref>{{Citation|title=Scrutinize Those In Power Every Day: Justice Chandrachud -Human Rights Day 2019 Speech|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mZQfCO4p1cs|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> where he highlighted the importance of democratic scrutiny, procedures and deliberation as an important facet of human rights protection. \n\nIn February 2020, he delivered the speech titled \u2018The hues that make India: from plurality to pluralism'<ref>{{Citation|title=Democracy's true test is the ability to allow individuals to voice their opinion:Justice Chandrachud|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oIW4fhXZMeg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> at the P D Desai Memorial Lecture in Gujarat. He stated:<blockquote>\u2026the employment of state machinery to curb dissent instils fear and creates a chilling atmosphere on free speech which violates the rule of law and detracts from the constitutional vision of a pluralist society\u2026The true test of a democracy is its ability to ensure the creation and protection of spaces where every individual can voice their opinion without the fear of retribution\u2026A state committed to the rule of law ensures that the state apparatus is not employed to curb legitimate and peaceful protest but to create spaces conducive for deliberation. Within the bounds of law, liberal democracies ensure that their citizens enjoy the right to express their views in every conceivable manner, including the right to protest and express dissent against prevailing laws. The blanket labelling of such dissent as \u2018anti-national\u2019 or \u2018anti-democratic\u2019 strikes at the heart of our commitment to the protection of constitutional values and the promotion of a deliberative democracy.</blockquote>In an impassioned appeal to pluralism and the celebration of diversity, he stated:<blockquote>The framers of the Constitution rejected the notion of a Hindu India and a Muslim India. They recognised only the Republic of India\u2026A united India is not one characterized by a single identity devoid of its rich plurality, both of cultures and of values. National unity denotes a shared culture of values and a commitment to the fundamental ideals of the Constitution in which all individuals are guaranteed not just the fundamental rights but also conditions for their free and safe exercise. Pluralism depicts not merely a commitment to the preservation of diversity, but a commitment to the fundamental postulates of individual and equal dignity. In this sense, pluralism furthers the basic postulates of the Constitution and nourishes and provides content to the goal of national unity...No single individual or institution can claim a monopoly over the idea of India\u2026what is of utmost relevance today is our ability and commitment to preserve, conserve and build on the rich pluralistic history we have inherited.</blockquote>The speech was delivered in the backdrop<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/latest/953264/labelling-dissent-as-anti-national-strikes-at-the-heart-of-democracy-says-justice-chandrachud|title=Labelling dissent as \u2018anti-national\u2019 strikes at the heart of democracy, says Justice Chandrachud|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> of the nationwide protests against the [[Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019]]. Another judge of the Supreme Court, Justice Deepak Gupta cited<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/sc-judge-opposing-govt-cant-be-labelled-anti-national-1649651-2020-02-25|title=SC judge says opposing govt can't be labelled as anti-national|last=DelhiFebruary 25|first=Indo-Asian News Service New|last2=February 25|first2=2020UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20|last3=Ist|first3=2020 01:49}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/sc-judge-says-opposing-govt-cant-be-labelled-as-antinational/1742712|title=SC judge says opposing govt can''t be labelled as anti-national|website=https://www.outlookindia.com/|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/judiciary/right-to-dissent-most-important-majoritarianism-is-antithesis-of-democracy-sc-judge-gupta/370054/|title=Right to dissent most important, majoritarianism is antithesis of democracy: SC judge Gupta|last=Roy|first=Debayan|date=2020-02-24|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> his speech at a function organised by the Supreme Court Bar Association and endorsed his views. The speech was widely commended<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.barandbench.com/news/litigation/state-cannot-claim-monopoly-over-values-that-define-our-plural-society-dy-chandrachud-j-on-why-dissent-is-important|title=State cannot claim monopoly over values that define our plural society: DY Chandrachud J. on why dissent is important|last=Bench|first=Bar &|website=Bar and Bench - Indian Legal news|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indialegallive.com/top-news-of-the-day/news/dissent-not-anti-national-says-justice-dy-chandrachud-89239|title=Dissent Not Anti-National excerpts/ Justice PD Desai Memorial Lecture 2020|last=Legal|first=India|date=2020-02-22|website=India Legal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/blanket-labelling-of-dissent-as-antinational-hurts-ethos-of/1735088|title=Blanket labelling of dissent as anti-national hurts ethos of|website=https://www.outlookindia.com/|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://punemirror.indiatimes.com/news/india/dissent-a-safety-valve-justice-chandrachud/articleshow/74156371.cms|title=Dissent a safety valve: Justice Chandrachud|last=Feb 16|first=PTI {{!}} Updated:|last2=2020|website=Pune Mirror|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20|last3=Ist|first3=08:07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/hindu-india-and-a-muslim-indiajustice-chandrachud-152796|title='The Framers of Constitution Rejected The Notion of a Hindu India And a Muslim India':Justice Chandrachud [Read Full Text Of Speech]|last=NETWORK|first=LIVELAW NEWS|date=2020-02-16|website=www.livelaw.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> with some hailing the observations in the speech as a plea to protect the right to dissent in a free and democratic society.\n\n==Notable judgments==\n\nAs a judge of the Supreme Court, Justice Chandrachud has been on the highest number of Constitution Benches (five judges or more) constituted to hear matters before the Indian Supreme Court.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.barandbench.com/columns/constituting-constitution-benches-of-the-supreme-court-an-analysis|title=Constituting Constitution Benches of the Supreme Court: An analysis|last=Bench|first=Bar &|website=Bar and Bench - Indian Legal news|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> During his tenure at the Supreme Court, he has delivered a large number of landmark judgements on Indian constitutional law, comparative constitutional law, human rights law, gender justice, public interest litigation, commercial law and criminal law.\n\n=== Privacy ===\nForemost among his notable judgments is his authorship of the lead opinion in [[Justice K. S. Puttaswamy (Retd.) and Anr. vs Union Of India And Ors.]] as part of a unanimous nine-judge Bench decision of the Indian Supreme Court which affirmed that the right to privacy is a constitutionally guaranteed right under the Indian Constitution.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2012/35071/35071_2012_Judgement_24-Aug-2017.pdf|title=Privacy judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Justice Chandrachud grounded the right to privacy in dignity, liberty, autonomy, bodily and mental integrity, self-determination and across a spectrum of protected rights. Writing for himself and three other judges, he stated:<blockquote>Dignity cannot exist without privacy. Both reside within the inalienable values of life, liberty and freedom which the Constitution has recognised. Privacy is the ultimate expression of the sanctity of the individual. It is a constitutional value which straddles across the spectrum of fundamental rights and protects for the individual a zone of choice and self-determination.<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>One expert on constitutional law hailed the decision<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://indconlawphil.wordpress.com/2017/08/27/the-supreme-courts-right-to-privacy-judgment-i-foundations/|title=The Supreme Court\u2019s Right to Privacy Judgment \u2013 I: Foundations|last=Bhatia|first=Gautam|date=2017-08-27|website=Indian Constitutional Law and Philosophy|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> as \u201ca historic and landmark verdict of our times\u201d which \u201cwill have a profound impact upon our legal and constitutional landscape for years to come.\u201d He stated that the:<blockquote>\u2026judgment deserves to be a landmark, not only in the annals of Indian constitutional jurisprudence, but across the world. The verdict locates privacy in the grand sweep of democracy and within the core human values of autonomy, dignity, and freedom, while also placing it within the realm of the concrete, the flesh-and-blood relationship between the individual and the State.<ref name=\":1\" /></blockquote>The judgment is also noteworthy for Justice Chandrachud\u2019s observations on sexual autonomy and privacy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/law/justice-chandrachud-judgment-right-to-privacy|title=Key Highlights of Justice Chandrachud's Judgment in the Right to Privacy Case|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In 2013, a two judge Bench of the Supreme Court of India in [[Suresh Kumar Koushal v. Naz Foundation]] upheld [[Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code]] which criminalized carnal intercourse against the order of nature. Justice Chandrachud referred to the decision as striking \u201ca discordant note which directly bears upon the evolution of the constitutional jurisprudence on the right to privacy.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> He observed that the decision was wrong as \u201cthe purpose of elevating certain rights to the stature of guaranteed fundamental rights is to insulate their exercise from the disdain of majorities, whether ''legislative or popular''.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> He concluded by disagreeing \u201cwith the manner in which Koushal has dealt with the privacy \u2013 dignity-based claims of LGBT persons\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> and held that:<blockquote>The test of popular acceptance does not furnish a valid basis to disregard rights which are conferred with the sanctity of constitutional protection.\u00a0 Discrete and insular minorities face grave dangers of discrimination for the simple reason that their views, beliefs or way of life does not accord with the \u2018mainstream\u2019. Yet in a democratic constitution founded on the rule of law, their rights are as sacred as those conferred on other citizens to protect their freedoms and liberties. Sexual orientation is an essential attribute of privacy. Discrimination against an individual on the basis of sexual orientation is deeply offensive to the dignity and self-worth of the individual.<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>The above observations were later instrumental<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/law/justice-chandrachud-judgment-right-to-privacy|title=Key Highlights of Justice Chandrachud's Judgment in the Right to Privacy Case|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|date=2015-06-05|title=Queer Rights and the Puttaswamy Judgment|url=https://www.epw.in/journal/2017/51/privacy-after-puttaswamy-judgment/queer-rights-and-puttaswamy-judgment.html|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|language=en|volume=52|issue=51|pages=7\u20138}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rsrr.in/2018/11/16/implications-puttaswamy-aadhar-section-377/|title=IMPLICATIONS OF JUSTICE K.S PUTTASWAMY CASE: AADHAR, SECTION-377 AND MORE - RGNUL Student Research Review (RSRR)|date=2018-11-16|website=RGNUL  Student Research  Review (RSRR)|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indconlawphil.wordpress.com/2017/08/31/the-supreme-courts-right-to-privacy-judgment-v-privacy-and-decisional-autonomy/|title=The Supreme Court\u2019s Right to Privacy Judgment \u2013 V: Privacy and Decisional Autonomy|last=Bhatia|first=Gautam|date=2017-08-31|website=Indian Constitutional Law and Philosophy|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalfreedomofexpression.columbia.edu/cases/puttaswamy-v-india/|title=Puttaswamy v. India|website=Global Freedom of Expression|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> in the judgment of the Supreme Court declaring Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code unconstitutional.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article24880700.ece/binary/Sec377judgment.pdf|title=Section 377 Judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> His opinion is also celebrated for expressly overruling the ADM Jabalpur v. Shiv Kant Shukla (Habeas Corpus) case in which the lead opinion was written by the father of Justice Chandrachud - former Chief Justice of India [[V. Y. Chandrachud]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livelaw.in/rare-moment-history-justice-d-y-chandrachud-overrules-fathers-judgment-adm-jabalpur-case/|title=A Rare Moment In History: Justice D.Y.Chandrachud Overrules His Father\u2019s Judgment In ADM Jabalpur Case|last=Network|first=LiveLaw News|date=2017-08-24|website=www.livelaw.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Abraham|first=Rohan|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/chandrachud-vs-chandrachud-sc-judge-confident-his-father-would-have-concurred-on-adm-jabalpur-verdict/articleshow/71736077.cms?from=mdr|title=Chandrachud vs Chandrachud: SC judge confident his father would have concurred on ADM Jabalpur verdict|date=2019-10-24|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Free Speech ===\nJustice Chandrachud has termed dissent as \u201cthe safety valve of democracy\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Politics/SiXRDqBThdK92lfR0CRyEP/Dissent-is-the-safety-valve-of-democracy-says-SC.html|title=Dissent is the safety valve of democracy, says SC|last=Ghadyalpatil|first=Shaswati Das ,Abhiram|date=2018-08-29|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/dissent-is-the-safety-valve-of-a-democracy-justice-chandrachud/story-1vOft3QfRvszjGuBBWSuLI.html|title=\u2018Dissent is the safety valve of a democracy\u2019: Justice Chandrachud|date=2020-02-15|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/justice-d-y-chandrachud-caa-protest-democracy-anti-national-6269831/|title=Dissent is \u2018safety valve\u2019 of democracy: Justice Chandrachud|date=2020-02-15|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and has authored judgments upholding the right to the freedom of speech in numerous cases. In Indibility Creative Pvt Ltd v State of West Bengal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2019/8409/8409_2019_Judgement_11-Apr-2019.pdf|title=Indibility Creative Pvt Ltd Judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, he authored a judgment which imposed a fine on the State of West Bengal and granted remedial compensation for disallowing the screening of the political satire ''Bhobishyoter Bhoot'' through extra-constitutional measures. The Court had, by an interim order, directed that there must be no bar on the screening of the movie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://punemirror.indiatimes.com/news/india/ensure-screening-of-anik-duttas-bhobishyoter-bhoot-supreme-court-to-west-bengal-govt/articleshow/68430662.cms|title=Ensure screening of Anik Dutta's Bhobishyoter Bhoot: Supreme Court to West Bengal govt|last=Nag|first=Jayatri NagJayatri|last2=Mar 15|first2=Mumbai Mirror {{!}} Updated:|website=Pune Mirror|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20|last3=2019|last4=Ist|first4=20:33}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/supreme-court-political-class-puzzle-on-bhobishyoter-bhoot/cid/1688003|title=Supreme Court political-class puzzle on Bhobishyoter Bhoot|website=www.telegraphindia.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In the final judgment, Justice Chandrachud held that even if there was any apprehension of public discontent, police protection must be provided instead of prohibiting the display of the movie. The judgment is noteworthy<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://indconlawphil.wordpress.com/2019/04/14/making-the-path-by-walking-the-supreme-courts-film-censorship-judgment/|title=Making the Path by Walking: The Supreme Court\u2019s Film Censorship Judgment|last=Bhatia|first=Gautam|date=2019-04-14|website=Indian Constitutional Law and Philosophy|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> for its recognition of the positive duty on the State to protect the freedom of speech and expression. He held that:<blockquote>Free speech cannot be gagged for fear of the mob\u2026Political freedoms impose a restraining influence on the state by carving out an area in which the state shall not interfere. Hence, these freedoms are perceived to impose obligations of restraint on the state. But, apart from imposing \u2018negative\u2019 restraints on the state these freedoms impose a positive mandate as well. In its capacity as a public authority enforcing the rule of law, the state must ensure that conditions in which these freedoms flourish are maintained. In the space reserved for the free exercise of speech and expression, the state cannot look askance when organized interests threaten the existence of freedom. The state is duty bound to ensure the prevalence of conditions in which of those freedoms can be exercised. The instruments of the state must be utilized to effectuate the exercise of freedom.</blockquote>The judgment was widely hailed<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/judiciary/how-sc-defended-freedom-of-speech-by-pulling-up-mamata-govt-for-blocking-satirical-film/220358/|title=How SC defended freedom of speech by pulling up Mamata govt for blocking satirical film|last=Jain|first=Ritika|date=2019-04-11|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thelogicalindian.com/news/sc-fines-wb-govt/|title=Free Speech Cannot Be Gagged': SC Fines Mamata Govt Rs 20 Lakh For 'Virtual Ban' On Movie|last=Indian|first=The Logical|date=2019-04-12|website=thelogicalindian.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/pay-rs-20-lakh-to-producer-supreme-court-tells-mamata-government/story-QejpUcjZpWlYFJcTrc8SdP.html|title=Pay Rs 20 lakh to producer, Supreme Court tells Mamata government|date=2019-04-12|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/india-news-sc-imposes-rs-20-lakh-fine-on-mamata-govt-for-ban-on-film-bhobishyoter-bhoot/328517|title=Supreme Court Imposes Rs 20 Lakh Fine On Mamata Govt For 'Virtual Ban' On Film 'Bhobishyoter Bhoot'|website=https://www.outlookindia.com/|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> for preventing the censorship of free speech and limiting its exceptions strictly to the grounds mentioned in Article 19(2) of the Constitution. \n\nIn Romila Thapar & Ors. v. Union of India & Ors, Justice Chandrachud dissented with the majority which refused to constitute a Special Investigation Team to probe the case concerning the arrest of five activists in connection with the [[2018 Bhima Koregaon violence]] and held that in light of the particular circumstances of the case, the constitution of a Special Investigation Team was necessary to ensure a fair and impartial investigation.\n\n=== Gender Justice ===\n\n==== Sabarimala verdict ====\nJustice Chandrachud has authored several landmark judgments on gender justice that call for a \u2018change in mindsets\u2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.barandbench.com/news/litigation/change-mindset-to-bring-true-equality-in-army-sc-holds-permanent-commission-should-be-available-to-all-women-officers|title=Change mindset to bring true equality in Army: SC holds Permanent Commission should be available to all women officers|last=Emmanuel|first=Meera|website=Bar and Bench - Indian Legal news|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> as well as affirm the equal entitlements of women under the Constitution. In Indian Young Lawyers Association v. State of Kerala<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2006/18956/18956_2006_Judgement_28-Sep-2018.pdf|title=Sabarimala judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, he authored a concurring judgment holding that the practice of prohibiting women of menstruating age from entering the [[Sabarimala]] temple was discriminatory and violated the fundamental rights of women. In his judgment, he highlighted that \u201cthe individual right to the freedom of religion was not intended to prevail over but was subject to the overriding constitutional postulates of equality, liberty and personal freedoms recognised in the other provisions of Part III.\u201d<ref name=\":3\" /> He held that:<blockquote>The Court must lean against granting constitutional protection to a claim which derogates from the dignity of women as equal holders of rights and protections\u2026 Does the Constitution permit this as basis to exclude women from worship? Does the fact that a woman has a physiological feature \u2013 of being in a menstruating age \u2013 entitle anybody or a group to subject her to exclusion from religious worship? The physiological features of a woman have no significance to her equal entitlements under the Constitution\u2026 To exclude women is derogatory to an equal citizenship.</blockquote>His opinion was widely celebrated<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indconlawphil.wordpress.com/2018/09/29/the-sabarimala-judgment-iii-justice-chandrachud-and-radical-equality/|title=The Sabarimala Judgment \u2013 III: Justice Chandrachud and Radical Equality|last=Bhatia|first=Gautam|date=2018-09-29|website=Indian Constitutional Law and Philosophy|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Rajagopal|first=Krishnadas|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/sabarimala-verdict-justice-chandrachud-calls-to-balance-group-rights-with-individual-freedoms/article25074121.ece|title=Sabarimala verdict: Justice Chandrachud calls to balance group rights with individual freedoms|date=2018-09-28|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> or recognizing that denying entry into temples to women on the basis of physiology amounted to a constitutionally prohibited practice of untouchability under Article 17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/sabarimala-temple-ban-because-of-menstruation-utterly-unconstitutional-supreme-court-1923609|title=Sabarimala Ban \"A Form Of Untouchability\", Says Justice Chandrachud|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forwardpress.in/2018/10/sabarimala-ayyappa-temple-justice-chandrachud-eng/|title=Exclusion of women from Sabarimala amounts to untouchability: Justice Chandrachud|last=\u091d\u093e|first=Ashok Jha \u0905\u0936\u094b\u0915|date=2018-10-06|website=Forward Press|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/purification-ritual-at-sabarimala-appears-to-violate-ban-on-untouchability-undermines-dy-chandrachuds-observations-in-28-sept-sc-verdict-5826081.html|title='Purification' ritual at Sabarimala appears to violate ban on untouchability, undermines DY Chandrachud's observations in 28 Sept SC verdict|website=Firstpost|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> He stated that \u201cthe social exclusion of women, based on menstrual status, is a form of untouchability, which is contrary to constitutional values. Notions of \u2018purity\u2019 and \u2018pollution\u2019, which stigmatise individuals, have no place in a constitutional order.\u201d<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nFollowing protests against the judgment in the State of Kerala<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-46744142|title=India state paralysed amid temple protest|date=2019-01-03|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/culture/2019/01/sabarimala-temple-india-kerala-protests/|title=Women visited this sacred temple. Then violent protests broke out. Why?|date=2019-01-08|website=Culture|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/sabarimala-unrest-kerala-activist-dies-in-clash-hartal-today-1422363-2019-01-03|title=Sabarimala protests: Activist succumbs to injuries, Kerala on edge after 2 women enter temple|last=ThiruvananthapuramJanuary 3|first=India Today Web Desk|last2=January 3|first2=2019UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20|last3=Ist|first3=2019 11:07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/protests-in-kerala-after-two-women-enter-sabarimala-temple/articleshow/67347043.cms?from=mdr|title=Protests in Kerala as 2 women enter Sabarimala temple, state-wide shutdown tomorrow|date=2019-01-02|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/01/tens-thousands-protest-india-sabarimala-temple-190101140533525.html|title=Tens of thousands protest in India over Sabarimala temple|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>, a five judge Bench of the Indian Supreme Court, while hearing a review petition against the judgment in November 2019, decided to refer the matter to a larger Bench. Justice Chandrachud and Justice Nariman (who were both part of the original Bench that passed the majority judgment) dissented<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/issues-not-before-this-court-2-who-differ-6120274/|title=Sabarimala dissenting view: What Justices Nariman, Chandrachud said|date=2019-11-15|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/to-review-or-not-is-only-narrow-question-rest-later-the-2-in-3-2-6120506/|title=Sabarimala: To review or not is only narrow question, rest later: The 2 in 3-2|date=2019-11-15|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and held that the parameters for the exercise of the review jurisdiction of the Court had not been met.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/sabarimala-let-big-bench-decide-larger-issues-essential-religious-practices-supreme-court-6120529/|title=Sabarimala review plea: Let big bench decide larger issues, essential religious practices, rules SC|date=2019-11-15|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==== Adultery ====\nIn Joseph Shine v Union of India<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2017/32550/32550_2017_Judgement_27-Sep-2018.pdf|title=Joseph Shine Judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> he authored a concurring judgment declaring the provision of the Indian Penal Code which concerned the [[adultery law in India]] unconstitutional. Emphasizing the constitutional commitment to equality and dignity, he held that:<blockquote>The creation of a just, egalitarian society is a process. It often involves the questioning and obliteration of parochial social mores which are antithetical to constitutional morality\u2026The ability to make choices within marriage and on every aspect concerning it is a facet of human liberty and dignity which the Constitution protects\u2026 Implicit in seeking to privilege the fidelity of women in a marriage, is the assumption that a woman contracts away her sexual agency when entering a marriage. That a woman, by marriage, consents in advance to sexual relations with her husband or to refrain from sexual relations outside marriage without the permission of her husband is offensive to liberty and dignity. Such a notion has no place in the constitutional order. Sexual autonomy constitutes an inviolable core of the dignity of every individual.<ref name=\":4\" /></blockquote>His concurring opinion was celebrated for its emphasis on the sexual autonomy of women even within the bounds of a marital relationship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.barandbench.com/news/marital-rape-debate-justice-dy-chandrachud-right-say-no-marriage|title=Marital Rape Debate: Justice DY Chandrachud on Right to say \u201cno\u201d after Marriage|last=Krishnan|first=Murali|website=Bar and Bench - Indian Legal news|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/husband-not-the-master-of-his-wife-supreme-court-scraps-150-year-old-law-made-adultery-crime/story/282918.html|title='Husband not the master of his wife': Supreme Court scraps 150-year-old law that made adultery a crime|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> He held that:<blockquote>\u2026. in adjudicating on the rights of women, the Court is not taking on a paternalistic role and \u201cgranting\u201d rights. The Court is merely interpreting the text of the Constitution to re-state what is already set in ink \u2014 women are equal citizens of this nation, entitled to the protections of the Constitution. Any legislation which results in the denial of these Constitutional guarantees to women, cannot pass the test of Constitutionality.<ref name=\":4\" /></blockquote>It is reported<ref>{{Cite news|last=India|first=Press Trust of|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/married-women-have-sexual-autonomy-like-right-to-say-no-sc-118080201433_1.html|title=Married women have sexual autonomy like right to say 'no': SC|date=2018-08-02|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/supreme-court-signal-on-marital-rape-consent-sexual-autonomy-in-marriage-are-key-values-5377501/|title=Supreme Court signal on marital rape: Consent, sexual autonomy in marriage are key values|date=2018-09-28|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> that the above observations have a significant bearing on the law employed for the [[restitution of conjugal rights]] as well as the exception carved out in law from criminalizing marital rape. Interestingly, this case was the second case where Justice Chandrachud overruled<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/adultery-law-justice-dy-chandrachud-overturns-another-judgment-by-father-yv-chandrachud-1350758-2018-09-27|title=Adultery law: Justice DY Chandrachud overturns another judgment by his father|last=DelhiSeptember 27|first=Prabhash K. Dutta New|last2=September 27|first2=2018UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20|last3=Ist|first3=2018 23:37}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/supreme-court-verdict-on-adultery-justice-dy-chandrachud-does-it-again-overrules-fathers-judgment-5277261.html|title=Supreme Court verdict on adultery: Justice DY Chandrachud does it again, overrules father's judgment|website=Firstpost|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-in/news/newsindia/adultery-law-justice-dy-chandrachud-overturns-another-judgment-by-his-father/ar-BBNBY9c|title=Adultery law: Justice DY Chandrachud overturns another judgment by his father|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2018/sep/28/adultery-verdict-justice-chandrachud-overrules-his-father-y-v-chandrachuds-ruling-1878105.html|title=Adultery verdict: Justice Chandrachud overrules his father Y V Chandrachud's ruling|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livelaw.in/justice-chandrachud-does-it-again-overrules-fathers-33-year-old-judgment-on-adultery-law/|title=Justice Chandrachud Does It Again, Overrules His Father's 33 Year Old Judgment On Adultery Law [Read Judgment]|last=Sebastian|first=Manu|date=2018-09-27|website=www.livelaw.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> a decision of his father, former Chief Justice of India [[V. Y. Chandrachud]].\n\n==== Armed Forces ====\n\n===== Army =====\nIn 2020, he authored two landmark decisions in the realm of gender justice and the armed forces of the country. In The Secretary, Ministry of Defence v Babita Puniya<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2010/20695/20695_2010_8_1501_20635_Judgement_17-Feb-2020.pdf|title=Babita Puniya judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> he directing the government to consider all woman officers in the Army appointed on Short Service Commissions for the grant of Permanent Commissions on an equal basis with their male counterparts. The Union Government had contended that \u201cwomen are not employed on duties which are hazardous in nature unlike their male counterparts in the same Arm/Service.\u201d<ref name=\":5\" /> It was also contended that the \u201cinherent physiological differences between men and women preclude equal physical performances resulting in lower physical standards.\u201d<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn a section titled \u2018Stereotypes and women in the Armed Forces\u2019, he emphasized on the need for a change in mindsets and came down heavily on the submissions of the Union Government and held that:<blockquote>The submissions advanced\u2026are based on sex stereotypes premised on assumptions about socially ascribed roles of gender which discriminate against women. Underlying the statement that it is a \u201cgreater challenge\u201d for women officers to meet the hazards of service \u201cowing to their prolonged absence during pregnancy, motherhood and domestic obligations towards their children and families\u201d is a strong stereotype which assumes that domestic obligations rest solely on women. Reliance on the \u201cinherent physiological differences between men and women\u201d rests in a deeply entrenched stereotypical and constitutionally flawed notion that women are the \u201cweaker\u201d sex and may not undertake tasks that are \u201ctoo arduous\u201d for them. Arguments founded on the physical strengths and weaknesses of men and women and on assumptions about women in the social context of marriage and family do not constitute a constitutionally valid basis for denying equal opportunity to women officers\u2026If society holds strong beliefs about gender roles \u2013 that men are socially dominant, physically powerful and the breadwinners of the family and that women are weak and physically submissive, and primarily caretakers confined to a domestic atmosphere \u2013 it is unlikely that there would be a change in mindsets.<ref name=\":5\" /></blockquote>The judgment was hailed internationally<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51528141|title=India army takes 'great leap' towards equality|date=2020-02-17|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-india-women-military-idUSKBN20B1X4|title=India's top court orders equal roles for women in army|date=2020-02-17|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/sexism-in-indian-army-top-court-ruling-shatters-glass-ceiling-for-women-officers/a-52419901|title=Sexism in Indian army: Top court ruling shatters glass ceiling for women officers {{!}} DW {{!}} 18.02.2020|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche|website=DW.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and widely reported as a \u201clandmark verdict ending gender bias\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/feb/17/sc-directs-centre-to-grant-permanent-commission-to-women-officers-in-army-2104553.html|title=SC directs Centre to grant permanent commission to women army officers in landmark verdict ending gender bias|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Feb 2020|first=Times Now {{!}} 17|title=SC directs permanent commission to women officers in armed forces|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/sc-directs-permanent-commission-to-women-officers-in-armed-forces/videoshow/74170629.cms|access-date=2020-04-20|last2=Ist|first2=12:25 Pm}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/defence/women-to-get-permanent-commission-in-indian-army-heres-everything-about-the-scs-historic-judgement/1870295/|title=Women to get permanent commission in Indian Army! Here\u2019s everything about the SC\u2019s historic judgement|date=2020-02-17|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/theprint-essential/women-arent-adjuncts-what-sc-said-while-granting-permanent-commission-to-women-in-army/366907/|title='Women aren't adjuncts' \u2014 what SC said while granting permanent commission to women in Army|last=M|first=Apoorva|last2=hani|date=2020-02-17|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> which is \u201cagainst deeply embedded patriarchal mindsets and strong institutional biases.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/editorials/women-in-indian-army-supreme-court-verdict-6274777/|title=In her own right|date=2020-02-19|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> At the International Judicial Conference hosted by India on the \u2018Judiciary and the Changing World\u2019, which saw the participation of Chief Justices and judges from over 23 countries, the President of India welcomed the judgment and commended it for its \u201cprogressive social transformation\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://164.100.117.97/WriteReadData/userfiles/International%20Judicial%20Conference23022019.pdf|title=Speech of the President at the IJC 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n===== Navy =====\nA short time thereafter, he authored the judgment in Union of India v Ld. Cdr. Annie Nagaraja<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2015/35837/35837_2015_3_1502_21539_Judgement_17-Mar-2020.pdf|title=Annie Nagaraja Judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> wherein the Court directed a similar relief to be granted to women sailors in the Indian Navy. The Court noted the submission of the Union Government that \u201ccertain avenues such as sea-sailing duties are ill-suited for women officers as there is no return to the base\u201d and that \u201cNavy ships of today are not structured nor have the infrastructure to accommodate women sailors alongside men sailors\u201d and rejected these submissions as \u201cillusory and without any foundation\u201d.<ref name=\":6\" /> He held that:<blockquote>A hundred and one excuses are no answer to the constitutional entitlement to dignity, which attaches to every individual irrespective of gender, to fair and equal conditions of work and to a level playing field. A level playing field ensures that women have the opportunity to overcome their histories of discrimination with the surest of responses based on their competence, ability and performance.<ref name=\":6\" /></blockquote>The judgment received similar international attention<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.laht.com/article.asp?ArticleId=2490469&CategoryId=12395|title=Latin American Herald Tribune - \u2018End Gender Stereotypes\u2019: Indian Court Rules in Favor of Women Navy Officers|website=www.laht.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and was widely reported upon in national media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/after-army-supreme-court-grants-permanent-commission-to-women-officers-in-navy/articleshow/74667440.cms?from=mdr|title=After Army, Supreme Court grants permanent commission to women officers in Navy|date=2020-03-17|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/women-sail-with-same-efficiency-sc-says-yes-to-permanent-commission-for-women-in-navy/382258/|title=\u2018Women sail with same efficiency\u2019 \u2014 SC says yes to permanent commission for women in Navy|last=Roy|first=Debayan|date=2020-03-17|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/sc-grants-permanent-commission-to-women-in-indian-navy-11584423945637.html|title=SC rules in favour of permanent commission for women officers in Navy|last=Bindra|first=Japnam|date=2020-03-17|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/after-army-supreme-court-grants-permanent-commission-to-women-officers-in-navy/articleshow/74667440.cms|title=After Army, Supreme Court grants permanent commission to women officers in Navy|date=2020-03-17|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hwnews.in/uncategorized/after-army-way-for-permanent-commission-to-women-in-navy-cleared-by-sc/127932|title=After Army, Way For Permanent Commission To Women In Navy Cleared by SC|last=Desk|first=News|date=2020-03-19|website=HW English|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/defence/boost-for-women-in-indian-navy-supreme-court-allows-permanent-commission-details/1900480/|title=Boost for women in Indian Navy! Supreme Court allows permanent commission; details|date=2020-03-17|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/mar/17/first-army-now-navy-supreme-court-nods-yes-to-permanent-commission-for-women--2117769.html|title=First Army, now Navy: Supreme Court nods yes to permanent commission for women|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestatesman.com/india/sail-efficiently-males-sc-grants-permanent-commission-women-officers-navy-1502866895.html|title='Can sail as efficiently as males': SC grants permanent commission to women officers in Navy|date=2020-03-17|website=The Statesman|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/women-equal-to-men-sc-grants-women-permanent-commission-in-navy/1771246|title=''Women equal to men'': SC grants women permanent commission in Navy|website=https://www.outlookindia.com/|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==== Sexual Harassment at the workplace ====\nRecently, he authored a judgment which affirmed affirming that sexual harassment at the workplace violates the fundamental rights of women guaranteed under the Indian Constitution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/sexual-harassment-at-workplace-is-affront-to-rights-of-woman-sc/1757982|title=Sexual harassment at workplace is affront to rights of woman: SC|website=https://www.outlookindia.com/|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> The verdict was based on a complaint made by a senior officer of the Punjab and Sind Bank that she was transferred out from Indore to Jabalpur because she had complained about irregularities and corruption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/sexual-harassment-affront-to-rights-of-woman-employee-supreme-court-812784.html|title=Sexual harassment affront to rights of woman employee: Supreme Court|date=2020-03-11|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> The woman, a chief manager and Scale IV officer, said she was also allegedly sexually harassed by her senior officer. He held that:<blockquote>Sexual harassment at the workplace is an affront to the fundamental rights of a woman to equality under Articles 14 and 15 and her right to live with dignity under Article 21 of the Constitution as well as her right to practice any profession or to carry on any occupation, trade or business\u2026 There can be no manner of doubt that the respondent (woman officer) has been victimized. This is symptomatic of a carrot and sticks policy adopted to suborn the dignity of a woman who is aggrieved by unfair treatment at her workplace. The law cannot countenance this. The order of transfer was an act of unfair treatment and is vitiated by malafides.</blockquote>He directed the bank to send the woman employee back to the Indore branch and held that the bank may pass any other order only after she has completed a tenure of one year at the Indore branch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/latest/955827/sexual-harassment-at-workplace-violates-womens-fundamental-rights-supreme-court|title=Sexual harassment at workplace violates women\u2019s fundamental rights: Supreme Court|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Environment ===\nOne of Justice Chandrachud\u2019s most celebrated<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/opinion/in-perspective/failed-by-ngt-saved-by-sc-731335.html|title=Failed by NGT, saved by SC|date=2019-04-29|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=IANS|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/goa-activists-opposition-welcome-sc-order-on-airport-119032901261_1.html|title=Goa activists, Opposition welcome SC order on airport|date=2019-03-29|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.civilsocietyonline.com/environment/rainbow-warriors-in-goa-get-new-airport-eia-annulled/|title=Rainbow Warriors in Goa get new airport EIA annulled - Civil Society Magazine|website=www.civilsocietyonline.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> opinions in the sphere of environmental law is his judgment in Hanuman Laxman Aroskar v Union of India<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2018/43379/43379_2018_Judgement_29-Mar-2019.pdf|title=Mopa, Goa judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. A challenge was brought before the Supreme Court against the order of the National Green Tribunal upholding the grant of an Environmental Clearance to a proposed greenfield international airport at Mopa in Goa. A myriad of contentions were urged by the appellants questioning the grant of the clearance, which included the failure to make disclosures on forests and Ecologically Sensitive Zones as well as a faulty appraisal process and the use of erroneous sampling points. The Court observed the numerous deficiencies in the process leading to the grant of the clearance and directed that a rapid EIA be conducted afresh<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scconline.com/blog/post/2019/03/30/environmental-clearance-for-development-of-airport-at-mopa-goa-to-be-revisited/|title=Environmental Clearance for development of Airport at Mopa, Goa to be revisited|last=Bhardwaj|first=Prachi|date=2019-03-29|website=SCC Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/law-and-policy/sc-suspends-environmental-clearance-to-mopa-airport-asks-eac-to-revisit-decision|title=Supreme Court Suspends Environmental Clearance Granted To Goa\u2019s Mopa Airport|website=BloombergQuint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> by the project proponent. The Court highlighted that compliance with the core governing notification is mandatory in the following terms:<blockquote>The 2006 notification represents an independent code with the avowed objective of balancing the development agenda with the protection of the environment. An applicant cannot claim an EC, under the 2006 notification, based on substantial or proportionate compliance with the terms stipulated in the notification. The terms of the notification lay down strict standards that must be complied with by an applicant seeking an EC for a proposed project. The burden of establishing environmental compliance rests on a project proponent who intends to bring about a change in the existing state of the environment\u2026 There can be no gambles with the environment: a \u2018heads I win, tails you lose\u2019 approach is simply unacceptable; unacceptable if we are to preserve environmental governance under the rule of law.<ref name=\":7\" /></blockquote>The judgment is celebrated for advancing the \u2018environmental rule of law\u2019 and for providing hope for the protection of the environment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/goa-turbulence-throws-light-on-mega-projects-1556208292034.html|title=Goa turbulence throws light on mega projects|date=2019-04-25|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The judgment was also lauded by the United Nations Environment Program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iamrenew.com/environment/un-lauds-sc-decision-to-suspend-construction-of-controversial-goa-airport/|title=UN Lauds SC Decision To Suspend Construction of Goa Airport|date=2019-04-02|website=Renewable Energy and Environmental Sustainability in India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> In a separate section titled the \u2018Environmental Rule of Law\u2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://epaper.timesgroup.com/Olive/ODN/TimesOfIndia/shared/ShowArticle.aspx?doc=TOIM/2019/03/31&entity=Ar00907&sk=8A6A3A2D&mode=text#|title=SC quotes \u2018environmental rule of law\u2019, stalls Goa\u2019s Mopa airport - The Times Of India - Mumbai, 3/31/2019|website=epaper.timesgroup.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> the Court drew from vast literature<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/goa-turbulence-throws-light-on-mega-projects-1556208292034.html|title=Goa turbulence throws light on mega projects|date=2019-04-25|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> on environmental law which included the UN Sustainable Development Goals and the work of Amartya Sen and Dhvani Mehta to draw a link between the protection of the environment and the right to life under Article 21 of the Indian Constitution.\n\nIn Bangalore Development Authority v Mr Sudhakar Hegde,<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2019/8100/8100_2019_3_1503_21539_Judgement_17-Mar-2020.pdf|title=BDA judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> he authored a judgment directing the appellant to conduct a rapid EIA as a result of the numerous deficiencies in the process leading upto the grant of Environmental Clearance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/state/get-fresh-environmental-impact-study-for-prr-supreme-court-to-karnataka-govt-814825.html|title=Get fresh environmental impact study for PRR: Supreme Court to Karnataka govt|date=2020-03-18|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The Court noted the \u201cpatent contradiction\u201d in disclosing the existence of forest land to be diverted for the project connecting Tumkur Road to Hosur Road.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2020/mar/18/apex-court-raps-bda-over-prr-seeks-new-eco-study-2118183.html|title=Apex court raps BDA over PRR, seeks new eco-study|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/city/top-bengaluru-stories/take-fresh-environmental-clearance-for-8-lane-project-in-bengaluru-sc-to-bda-814629.html|title=Take fresh environmental clearance for 8-lane project in Bengaluru: SC to BDA|date=2020-03-17|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> In a section titled \u2018Courts and the Environment\u2019, he highlighted the importance of a broad-based approach to the protection of the environment in the following terms:<blockquote>The protection of the environment is premised not only on the active role of courts, but also on robust institutional frameworks within which every stakeholder complies with its duty to ensure sustainable development. A framework of environmental governance committed to the rule of law requires a regime which has effective, accountable and transparent institutions. Equally important is responsive, inclusive, participatory and representative decision making. Environmental governance is founded on the rule of law and emerges from the values of our Constitution. Where the health of the environment is key to preserving the right to life as a constitutionally recognized value under Article 21 of the Constitution, proper structures for environmental decision making find expression in the guarantee against arbitrary action and the affirmative duty of fair treatment under Article 14 of the Constitution.<ref name=\":8\" /></blockquote>Justice Chandrachud has also authored a judgment on the validity of grating ''ex post facto'' Environmental Clearances in Alembic Pharmaceuticals Ltd v Rohit Prajapati.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://main.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2016/2562/2562_2016_0_1501_21582_Judgement_01-Apr-2020.pdf|title=Alembic Judgment|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The erstwhile Ministry of Environmental and Forests had issued an administrative circular in 2002 envisaging the grant of ''ex post facto'' clearances to those industries that had failed to comply with the mandatory EIA notification of 1994. The ex post facto clearances granted to a group of drug and pharmaceutical companies located in Gujarat were challenged. Justice Chandrachud set aside the administrative circular of 2002 and noted that the concept of ''ex post facto'' ECs derogates from the fundamental principles of the environmental rule of law. He noted that the grant of ''ex post facto'' ECs was contrary to both the precautionary principle as well as the principal of sustainable development.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/sc-penalises-three-pharma-cos-asks-to-pay-fine-of-rs-10-cr-each-820450.html|title=SC penalises three pharma cos, asks to pay fine of Rs 10 Cr each|date=2020-04-02|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Justice Chandrachud noted that all the industries in question had made significant infrastructural investments. In this backdrop, he imposed a fine of Rs 10 crores each for the purpose of restitution and restoration of the environment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lawstreet.co/judiciary/industries-causing-pollution-asked-to-pay-compensation?refuid=ODAzM3w1MC42My4xNjAuMjE3fHNvb2xlZ2FsLmNvbQ==|title=Industries Causing Pollution Asked To Pay Rs. 30 Crore As Compensation For Preservation Of Environment: SC [Read Order]|last=Lawstreet|website=Lawstreet.co|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livelaw.in/environment/ex-post-facto-environmental-clearance-unsustainable-in-law-sc-154678|title='Ex Post Facto' Environmental Clearance Unsustainable In Law : SC [Read Judgment]|last=NETWORK|first=LIVELAW NEWS|date=2020-04-02|website=www.livelaw.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>  He held:<blockquote>Requirements such as conducting a public hearing, screening, scoping and appraisal are components of the decision-making process which ensure that the likely impacts of the industrial activity or the expansion of an existing industrial activity are considered in the decision-making calculus. Allowing for an ex post facto clearance would essentially condone the operation of industrial activities without the grant of an EC. In the absence of an EC, there would be no conditions that would safeguard the environment. Moreover, if the EC was to be ultimately refused, irreparable harm would have been caused to the environment. In either view of the matter, environment law cannot countenance the notion of an ex post facto clearance. This would be contrary to both the precautionary principle as well as the need for sustainable development.<ref name=\":9\" /></blockquote>\n\n== Others ==\nJustice Chandrachud has also been the voice of a strong dissent in notable cases. He wrote a dissenting opinion in the Aadhaar<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremecourtofindia.nic.in/supremecourt/2012/35071/35071_2012_Judgement_26-Sep-2018.pdf|title=Aadhaar}}</ref> case, where the majority upheld the constitutional validity of the largest biometric identity project in the world. Justice Chandrachud held the project to be unconstitutional and violative of fundamental rights. In Jindal Stainless Ltd. v. State of Haryana,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/jonew/judis/44300.pdf|title=Entry Tax}}</ref> a 9-judge Bench decision on the constitutional validity of entry tax imposed by states in India, Justice Chandrachud authored a dissenting opinion. He also wrote a dissent in Abhiram Singh v. CD Commachen,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/jonew/judis/44451.pdf|title=Abhiram Singh}}</ref> a case concerning the regulation of election speech, and in Santhini v. Vijaya Venkatesh<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2016/27362/27362_2016_Judgement_09-Oct-2017.pdf|title=Santhini}}</ref> on the question of the validity of video-conferencing in matrimonial and family cases. In Romila Thapar & Ors. v. Union of India & Ors,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2018/32319/32319_2018_Judgement_28-Sep-2018.pdf|title=Romila Thapar}}</ref> Justice Chandrachud dissented with the majority which refused to constitute a Special Investigation Team to probe the case concerning the arrest of five activists in connection with the Bhima Koregoan violence and held that in light of the particular circumstances of the case, the constitution of a Special Investigation Team was necessary to ensure a fair and impartial investigation.\n\nHe has also authored opinions in the decisions of Common Cause v. Union of India<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2005/9123/9123_2005_Judgement_09-Mar-2018.pdf|title=Common Cause}}</ref> legalising passive euthanasia and living wills, the ruling in Govt. of NCT of Delhi v. Union of India & Anr<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremecourtofindia.nic.in/pdf/LU/29357.pdf|title=NCT Delhi}}</ref> on the balance of powers between the Lt. Governor and the Chief Minister in the governance of the National Capital Territory, Kalpana Mehta & Ors. v. Union of India & Ors<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2012/36970/36970_2012_Judgement_09-May-2018.pdf|title=Kalpana Mehta}}</ref> which held that the reliance on Parliamentary Standing Committee Reports by Courts did not constitute a breach of Parliamentary privilege, and in Swapnil Tripathi v. Supreme Court of India,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2017/40426/40426_2017_Judgement_26-Sep-2018.pdf|title=Live-Streaming}}</ref> the judgment which allowed live streaming of Indian court cases. In his judgment regarding the construction of a new airport in Goa and resulting environmental law violations, the Environmental Clearance (EC) granted for the construction of the new airport at Mopa in Goa has been suspended until the Expert Appraisal Committee (EAC) revisits the recommendations made for the grant of an EC. The judgment is significant for developing the jurisprudence on \"environmental rule of law\" and its treatment of ecologically sensitive zones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2018/43379/43379_2018_Judgement_29-Mar-2019.pdf|title=In the Supreme Court of India Civil Appellate Jurisdiction}}</ref> In Indibility Creative Pvt Ltd v State of West Bengal,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2019/8409/8409_2019_Judgement_11-Apr-2019.pdf|title=Indibility Creative v. Govt. of West Bengal}}</ref> he authored a judgment which imposed a fine on the State of West Bengal and granted remedial compensation for not allowing the screening of&nbsp; the political satire ''Bhobishyoter Bhoot'', through extra-constitutional measures. The judgment is also noteworthy for its recognition of the positive duty of the State to protect the freedom of speech and expression. In B.K. Pavitra II v. Union of India,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sci.gov.in/supremecourt/2018/15655/15655_2018_Judgement_10-May-2019.pdf|title=B.K. Pavitra v. Union of India}}</ref> he authored a landmark judgement which upheld the constitutional validity of the Karnataka Extension of Consequential Seniority to Government Servants Promoted on the Basis of Reservation (to the Posts in the Civil Services of the State) Act 2018 &nbsp;which adopts the principle that consequential seniority is not an additional benefit but a consequence of the promotion which is granted to members of the Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes. The judgment was celebrated for undertaking a critical, nuanced analysis that favoured an inclusive definition of 'efficiency' and consequently 'merit', - one that is consistent with the principle of substantive equality, as opposed to formal equality.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070806180624/http://www.vmslaw.edu/sympo.htm Millennium laws For India Inc.---A symposium]\n* [http://lawcommissionofindia.nic.in/adr_conf/chandrachud3.pdf M E D I A T I O N \u2013 realizing the potential and designing. implementation strategies.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928170649/http://www.humanrightsinitiative.org/jc/papers/jc_2002/judges_papers/chandrachud_final.pdf First South Asian Regional Judicial Colloquium on Access to Justice]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070820184647/http://www.humanrightsinitiative.org/jc/papers/jc_2003/background_papers.htm CHRI: Judicial Colloquia Series on Access to Justice]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070702192624/http://www.interights.org/page.php?dir=News Justiciability of Economic, Social and Cultural Rights in the Pacific\u2014A judicial colloquium and workshop]\n* [http://www.allahabadhighcourt.in/service/judgeDetail.jsp?id=203|High Court of Judicature at Allahabad]\n\n{{Sitting Judges of the Supreme Court of India}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chandrachud, Dhananjaya Y.}}\n[[Category:20th-century Indian judges]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Faculty of Law, University of Delhi alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian solicitors]]\n[[Category:Judges of the Mumbai High Court]]\n[[Category:St. Columba's School, Delhi alumni]]\n[[Category:Chief Justices of the Allahabad High Court]]\n[[Category:Justices of the Supreme Court of India]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian judges]]\n", "name_user": "Charmanderrulez", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor edits on grammar and text.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dhananjaya_Y._Chandrachud"}
{"title_page": "Bush discography", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox artist discography\n|Artist       = [[Bush (British band)|Bush]]\n|Image        =  \n|Caption      = \n|Studio       = 7\n|Compilation  = 2\n|Video        = 2\n|Live         = 1\n|Music videos = 24\n|Singles      = 28\n}}\n\nThe [[discography]] of [[Bush (British band)|Bush]], an English [[Rock music|rock]] band, consists of 7 [[studio album]]s, 1 [[live album]], 2 [[compilation album]]s, and 28 [[Single (music)|singles]] released on [[Interscope Records]]. The band had released 4 studio albums before separating in 2002. They reunited in 2010 and have since released 3 albums.\n\n== Albums ==\n\n=== Studio albums ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album details\n! colspan=\"10\"| Peak chart positions \n! rowspan=\"2\"| [[Music recording sales certification|Certifications]]<ref name=\"CRIA\">Certifications for Bush's albums in Canada: \n*For \"Sixteen Stone\" {{cite web|url=http://www.musiccanada.com/GPSearchResult.aspx?st=Sixteen%20Stone&ica=False&sa=Bush&sl=&smt=0&sat=-1&ssb=Artist|title=Bush - Sixteen Stone|publisher=[[Canadian Recording Industry Association]]|accessdate=2011-12-21}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*For \"Razorblade Suitcase\" {{cite web|url=http://www.musiccanada.com/GPSearchResult.aspx?st=Razorblade%20Suitcase&ica=False&sa=Bush&sl=&smt=0&sat=-1&ssb=Artist|title=Bush - Razorblade Suitcase|publisher=[[Canadian Recording Industry Association]]|accessdate=2011-12-21}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*For \"The Science of Things\" {{cite web|url=http://www.musiccanada.com/GPSearchResult.aspx?st=The%20Science%20of%20Things&ica=False&sa=Bush&sl=&smt=0&sat=-1&ssb=Artist|title=Bush - The Science of Things|publisher=[[Canadian Recording Industry Association]]|accessdate=20